<P>If the performance of a writer thus di&s;tre&s;&s;ed is
not perfect, its faults ought &s;urely to be imputed to
a cau&s;e very different from want of genius, and
mu&s;t rather excite pity than provoke cen&s;ure.</P>
<P>But when under the&s;e di&s;couragements the tragedy
