<NOTE N="&ast;" PLACE="foot">Vol. I. p. 148. 186.</NOTE>prologue and epilogue, in which he touches on the
circum&s;tances of the author with great tenderne&s;s.</P>
<P>After all the&s;e ob&s;tructions and compliances, he
was only able to bring his play upon the &s;tage in the
&s;ummer, when the chief actors had retired, and the
re&s;t were in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the hou&s;e for their own
advantage. Among the&s;e, Mr. Savage was admitted
