<BODY>
<DIV1>
<PB REF="127">
<HEAD>LOVE IN A VEIL.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>ACT I. SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The Street.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> Charles Winlove <HI>and Don</HI> Philip <HI>meeting.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>DON Philip!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Charles Winlove! What miracle has
brought you here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why faith, 'tis a miracle owing to for|tune
&mdash;Have you heard what has happened to me at
Madrid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I heard of your unfortunate adventure
there, before I left it&mdash;How long have you been come
to Valencia?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>About a fortnight, and I only wait for
a fair wind to carry me to England.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'd advi&s;e you to make the be&s;t of your
way, for there was a rumour that orders wou'd be
&s;ent to the &s;ea-ports to put a &s;top to your pa&s;&s;age.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why this comes now of intriguing in
Spain&mdash;A man can't carry on an amour, but he
mu&s;t cut the throat of &s;ome jealous coxcomb or other
to cure him of his impertinence&mdash;But what other
news? I find you left Madrid later than I did&mdash;Is
my rival that I wounded, dead?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="128">
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>When I came away I heard that his life
was de&s;pair'd of.&mdash;And that the lady for whom your
quarrel began, was fled from her father's hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry for her &s;ake, for &s;he is every
way &s;o agreeable, that cou'd I learn to be con&s;tant,
'twou'd be only to her&mdash;But I find one love is &s;till
an antidote to expel another: For I have &s;een &s;uch
a beauty here in Valencia!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Another beauty! Sir Charles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, one &s;o charming, &s;o good-humour'd,
and &s;o witty, &s;he's enough to turn the re&s;olutions of
a Cynic&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is &s;he a woman of quality?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, I can't tell&mdash;Her appearance is
as yet like that of Cynthia in a cloud, for I have
never &s;een her but in a VEIL.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought to have heard that you'd have
been more cautious, Sir Charles&mdash;But I find you are
&s;till the &s;ame, and are re&s;olv'd to bear the frowns of
fortune with as much plea&s;ure as her &s;miles&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Don Philip, let cowards fear her,
and fools, her daily favourites, adore her&mdash;For my
part, love and friend&s;hip &s;hall &s;till be the darlings
of my &s;oul&mdash;And new plea&s;ures the continual bu&s;i|ne&s;s
of my life&mdash;But prithee, what &s;ort of company
have you here in Valencia?&mdash;For tho' I am return|ing
<PB N="9" REF="129">
to England, I am &s;o tir'd with politics, that
I perfectly nau&s;eate the conver&s;ation of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>How &s;o? Is there no other to be had
then?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>None! Politicians &s;tart out of every pro|fe&s;&s;ion,
and &s;tock-jobbers lies are the only di&s;cour&s;e
one can meet with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope the beaus don't turn politicians
in any nation&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>The beaus! Why the very women are
turn'd politicians&mdash;In &s;hort, the go&s;&s;iping of the
tea-table i as much in&s;ected as the &s;ociety of the
coffee-hou&s;es&mdash;How are you at this part of the globe?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>We are like the re&s;t of the world.&mdash;
Here are all manner of characters&mdash;Hu&s;bands that
are jealous of their honour, and wives that as craftily
betray it&mdash;For the ladies&mdash;Here's a compo&s;ition of
all nations&mdash;Some bea&s;t the affectation of the French;
&s;ome their own natural Spani&s;h pride; and others
the beauty and ob&s;tinancy of your Engli&s;h women&mdash;
Then for the men, here are from the formal gran|dees
to the extravagant fop; and from the cavaliers
of quality to the very fortune-hanter&mdash;In &s;hort, here
are all degrees what&s;oever&mdash;some of 'em rely upon
the merit of their riches, and others upon that of
their a&s;&s;urance&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="130">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;&s;urance is the mo&s;t thriving virtue of
the age. 'Tis a fortune for a courtier, and a pre|vailing
eloquence in a lover&mdash;But among&s;t the re&s;t,
What &s;ort of a man is your governor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>A man of quality, and one who&s;e innate
worth is an honour to the office he bears&mdash;Now I
think on't, he may be of &s;ervice to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, prithce which way?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has a daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is &s;he very hand&s;ome?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beautiful as an angel; and then for her
wit, 'tis as inchanting as her beauty; her repartees
are as quick as her eyes, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir. Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And when &s;hall I &s;ee her, Don Philip!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's to be my wife&mdash;For which purpo&s;e
I am come here to Valencia.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How coud'&s;t thou be &s;o ill-natur'd now,
to rai&s;e my fancy to &s;uch a pitch for this? What
&s;ervice can it be to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did not de&s;ign to help you to a mi&s;tre&s;s,
Sir Charles, I only had a mind to let you know my
intere&s;t with the governor; and I hope to win him
to intercede for your pardon, and to wink at your
&s;ecurity here.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! you are ever oblliging, Don Philip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a $word$ among&s;t friends.&mdash;I re|member
<PB N="11" REF="131">
in England, when I was oppre&s;s'd by
odds, you &s;av'd my life with hazard of your own&mdash;
Here I run no ri&s;que in the pre&s;ervation of yours&mdash;
But how d'ye intend to &s;pend the day?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have an a&s;&s;ignation, but the time is
not yet expir'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the mean time what &s;ay you to a gla&s;s
of good wine?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart&mdash;For 'tis &s;till my opi|nion,
that next to the chat of a lady at her tea-table,
there's no plea&s;ure like the &s;ociety of a friend over
a bottle.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh you are ever plea&s;ant, Sir Charles.&mdash;
But ha! Who comes here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis my &s;ervant!&mdash;Don Philip, you'll
excu&s;e me a little, I'll be with you immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee you are upon the &s;cent of an in|trigue!
Well, I won't interrupt you, when you've
done with your emi&s;&s;ary&mdash;follow me to the next
inn, where I'll wait for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do &s;o, I'll talk but a minute with my
man, and then I am your's over a bottle.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exit</HI> Don Philip.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> A&s;pin.</STAGE>
<P>So A&s;pin, What news have you brought me of the
lady in the VEIL?</P>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="132">
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>News! Sir; if I had accompli&s;h'd my ends,
I cou'd have brought you news and &s;ucce&s;s enough
to make your heart leap up to your mouth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look ye, Sirrah, don't tri&s;ie, my time's
too precious, by repeating what you only fancy you
cou'd have done; but tell me what &s;ucce&s;s you have
had in reality.&mdash;Did you dog the lady as I order'd
you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dog the lady! Ay, Sir, I have dog'd her to
&s;ome purpo&s;e! Well, I'll &s;ay no more; but if ex|pedition
and conduct can make a &s;tate&s;man, A&s;pin
may in time come to be di&s;tingui&s;h'd by a title.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, I can &s;carce doubt of your &s;ucce&s;s,
for I know thou art an excellent &s;etter upon occa|&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, and a runner too, a$ you'll find by the
&s;equel of the &s;tory&mdash;Look ye, Sir, you may remem|ber
you order'd me to watch the lady home; I
obey'd your commands, but &s;he perceiving my em|ployment,
led me through the mazes of &s;everal blind
alleys; notwith&s;tanding which, like an experienc'd
in&s;trument of the game, I &s;till kept as clo&s;e a &s;cent
after her, as hound after a co$ey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very pretty &s;imilitude!&mdash;But have you
hous'd her? Tell me that part of the &s;tory, A&s;pin!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hous'd her! No, Sir, I han't hous'd her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="133">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sirrah! Then what's the end of all
this mighty performance?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing at all, Sir!&mdash;In &s;hort, there fell out
an unlucky accident; for as I was hot in the pur|&s;uit,
I happen'd to &s;tumble upon a pebble, &s;prain'd
my ancle, and lo&s;t the &s;ight of her in a moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Sirrah, wou'd I cane you for the
di&s;appointment, but that I have other affairs in hand.
&mdash;Mark me, I am now going to drink a bottle with
a friend, in an hour I am to meet the lady at my
lodging; and if you don't look better to your po&s;t,
I'll break that ra&s;cally head of yours, Sirrah.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, to be &s;ure! What damnable lives do we
poor valets lead! if we &s;ucceed in the mo&s;t difficult
adventure, we do but our duty forfooth; but if we
fail, I'll break your head you ra&s;cal; hold, let me
think how &s;hall I retrieve my misfortunes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Studios.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Diego.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hi&s;t! Friend, do you live hereabouts?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hum! ha! Why what is that to you, friend,
where I live? I owe you nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I owe you a great deal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say you &s;o, Sir! Come, pay then, pay;&mdash;egad
<PB N="14" REF="134">
this fellow has mi&s;taken me for &s;omebody el&s;e; now if
I &s;hould luckily come in for a round &s;um that I have
no pretence to, faith 'twould be very welcome&mdash;But
as you was &s;aying, Sir, what do you owe me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>A great deal of re&s;pect, Sir, as you are a
fine gentleman, and all that, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Phough, pox, d'ye mean to banter me? If
that's all, I won't give a pin for your debt, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! But, Sir! you don't comprehend me;
my re&s;pect is but the prelude to &s;omething greater.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! To &s;omething greater! Egad this fellow
has the air of what we call in downright Engli&s;h
a pimp. Od&s;o! A&s;pin, thou art a made man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>The fellow &s;eems tickled with &s;ome imagi|nation
that may be of u&s;e to me, I'll &s;tudy to im|prove
it [<HI>A&s;ide</HI>]. But as I was &s;aying, Sir, may
not I be &s;o happy to know your lodging&mdash;Come,
don't &s;tand in your own light, I'll engage you &s;hall
be hand&s;omely rewarded by one greater than my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad it is &s;o&mdash;Some Seignora has fix'd her
affections upon me; what is &s;he, Sir; what is &s;he?&mdash;
Harkee, which part of me has tickled her lady&s;hip's
fancy? ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>As I gue&s;s'd; I'll humour him&mdash;I am under
an obligation not to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not to&mdash;What? Come, come, hang &s;ecrecy!
<PB N="15" REF="135">
Is it the broadne&s;s of my &s;houlders, the bigne&s;s of
my calves, or the air of my gait,&mdash;that has done
it? Ha? Od&s;o, now I think on't, I warrant the jade
has heard I am an Iri&s;hman&mdash;Ay, there it is faith
now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, you have hit it! Therefore, if you'll
let me &s;ee where you lodge, I'll bring a chair for
you in the evening, and convey you to the arms of
the mo&s;t beautiful Madona in all Valencia.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay! But upon &s;econd thoughts! I find I am
very unfit for &s;uch an adventure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mean! Why I mean that I ever had from
my cradle a damnable aver&s;ion to a pi&s;tol or a po|niard&mdash;Nay,
now I think on't, la&s;t night I had an
ugly dream about the noi&s;e of a pi&s;tol&mdash;But hang
dreams, they &s;hall never $right a man of my courage
&mdash;Know then, Sir, I live at yonder green rails: I am
but a valet, or &s;o, Sir, but in an hour I &s;hall be at
my lady's command&mdash;In the mean time I'll follow
the example of my ma&s;ter, and drink a bottle to
prepare my&s;elf for her &s;ervice.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>This fool has betray'd his ma&s;ter as I cou'd
wi&s;h&mdash;But now for my lord governor.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<DIV4 TYPE="scene">
<PB N="16" REF="136">
<HEAD>SCENE, The governor's hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Lorenzo</HI> with a letter, and <HI>Diego.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bring you this from Madrid, &s;ay you?&mdash;But
hold, let me peru&s;e it.</P>
<Q><P>&startq;An Engli&s;h cavalier, who has lately kill'd
a nobleman of Spain, is fled away with my
daughter; and, as I am inform'd, they
have taken their way to Valencia&mdash;I de&s;ire
you will lo&s;e no time in endeavouring to
&s;eize 'em&mdash;The bearer will give you a full
de&s;cription of both. I am yours,</P>
<P>From Madrid.</P>
<P>ALONZO.&endq;</P></Q>
<P>I take it kindly that my friend remembers me in
this misfortune&mdash;for I owe him many obligations&mdash;
Who is this cavalier?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is call'd Sir Charles Winlove; and he
undoubtedly &s;tole her, for &s;he was the cau&s;e of their
duel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where do you think he is?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I had ju&s;t now notice of his lodg|ing
from his own &s;ervant, and if you plea&s;e I'll pre|pare
officers in order to &s;eize him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do &s;o, and I'll go in per&s;on!
<STAGE>[<HI>Exit</HI> Diego.</STAGE>
<PB N="17" REF="137">
Unfortunate Alonzo! how unhappy is the man, the
honour of who&s;e family depends on a woman.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Leonora</HI> and <HI>Flora.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What makes you &s;o thoughtful, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you knew the contents of this paper, Leo|nora,
you wou'd not wonder that the cares of a father
&s;hou'd make me thoughtful.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;o, my lord? I hope I have not been
guilty of any thing to di&s;plea&s;e you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not as yet&mdash;But the duty of a parent is a
great weight; and where the lo&s;s of honour depends,
'tis to be fear'd more than the lo&s;s of life&mdash;I am in
ha&s;te at pre&s;ent, and mu&s;t defer this &s;ubject till
another opportunity&mdash;In the mean time take heed,
my Leonora.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am confus'd!&mdash;What does my father mean
by the lo&s;s of honour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am afraid, Madam, that he knows &s;ome of
your haunts, and therefore I'd advi&s;e you to be
cautious.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis hard that a Spani&s;h woman can't have
an amour, but &s;ome jealous-pated father or brother
mu&s;t interfere with the honour of his family. Now
I have heard, that the Engli&s;h women may take
what diver&s;ion they plea&s;e, and be rather celebrated
<PB N="18" REF="138">
for their beauty, than cen&s;ur'd.&mdash;Nay, that the very
wives may have a whole equipage of lovers, and be
the more admired by their hu&s;bands.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis the nature of the climate, Madam; as
in France the coquet is rather admir'd for her airs,
than cen&s;ur'd for her inclinations. Not but there's
detraction in both climates; but there 'tis a plea&s;ure
peculiar to the women, where &s;candal pa&s;&s;es for wit,
and one beauty ri&s;es on the falling reputation of
another. The men, unle&s;s the beaus, have nothing
to do with it; and tho&s;e no farther, than a little
raillery for their diver&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cou'd be as free as they had I the power&mdash;
For I have cho&s;e a per&s;on of my own liking, and
my father has contracted me to one that is indifferent
to me. Now, methinks, there's &s;uch a plea&s;ure in
the di&s;obedience, that it adds an eloquence to the
&s;uit of a lover.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Madam, d'ye con&s;ider that the nature
of this country is revenge&mdash;Here is none of the
carele&s;s brother, the indulgent father, nor the meek
animal, a hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis want of courage in our lovers to put a
good cu&s;tom in practice, otherwi&s;e the jealous fury
of a Spani&s;h Don might in time be moderated to
the content of a London citizen.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="19" REF="139">
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Madam, you have not &s;o much rea&s;on
to complain&mdash;Is not Don Philip, your intended hu&s;band,
a noble Spaniard, and as agreeable as the
Engli&s;h cavalier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh what a hideous compari&s;on have you
made! the Engli&s;h cavalier! Is he not all that a
woman can wi&s;h for? A man of gallantry&mdash;Beautiful
in his per&s;on, and agreeable in his conver&s;ation?
Are not all the per&s;ua&s;ive charms of wit upon his
tongue? Is he not, in &s;hort, an Engli&s;hman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is not Don Philip a man of honour? of a
gallant di&s;po&s;ition&mdash;And then he loves you as well
as the other.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, but then he is to be my hu&s;band, Flora;
and the pro&s;pect of a fore'd marriage eclip&s;es the
worth of a &s;uitor&mdash;Be&s;ides, my mother was an
Engli&s;hwoman&mdash;Therefore I am of &s;o gay a temper,
and &s;o naturally fond of liberty, that I can never be
confin'd to the humours of a jealous Spaniard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am convinc'd, Madam, by your inclinations
to the Engli&s;h cavalier, that beauty is totally owing
to fancy&mdash;But how came you acquainted with him
at fir&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you&mdash;You know when my father &s;ent
for me to Valencia, the people after my arrival
crowded to &s;ee me&mdash;I was admir'd by the men, and
<PB N="20" REF="140">
envy'd by the women&mdash;When I appear'd at church,
all were in a con&s;ternation&mdash;whi&s;pering, This is the
governor's daughter&mdash;till, contrary to my &s;ex, I was
almo&s;t tir'd with vanity it&s;elf&mdash;One day I went
VEIL'D into the walks to divert my&s;elf&mdash;There I
thought I &s;aw my father, but afterwards it prov'd
otherwi&s;e&mdash;Then I flew into a &s;ummer-hou&s;e to
avoid him&mdash;where I met this &s;tranger, who, &s;eeing
me in di&s;tre&s;s, proffer'd his a&s;&s;i&s;tance&mdash;I was pleas'd
with the compliment, and lik'd both his conver&s;ation
and his per&s;on&mdash;He pre&s;s'd to know me; but I refus'd
it&mdash;However, I have often &s;een him &s;ince, and mu&s;t
in &s;hort, according to appointment, meet him in|&s;tantly
again.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Madam, your father has agreed for
your marriage, and this apartment has received your
intended hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>A lady de&s;ires to &s;ee you, Madam,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is &s;he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never &s;aw her before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>De&s;ire her to walk in.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Fidelia VEIL'D.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I am come, tho' unknown, an
humble petitioner to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="141">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If 'tis a &s;ecret, I'll hear it alone, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, 'tis what a &s;ervant mu&s;t know, if
granted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>In what can I &s;erve you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>In giving refuge to an unfortunate per&s;on
&mdash;But ere I tell you my &s;tory, be pleas'd to peru&s;e
that letter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you are welcome upon the recom|mendation
of Theodo&s;ia&mdash;I hope &s;he's well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you, Madam, &s;he's very well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall be us'd with as much re&s;pect as
my&s;elf&mdash;She has here inform'd me, you're unfor|tunate;
but the particulars I am ignorant of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>That ta&s;k is left for me&mdash;which I &s;hall tell
you in a few words&mdash;I am the daughter of a noble|man,
who&s;e name, in re&s;pect to him, I conceal&mdash;
I lov'd, unknown to him, an Engli&s;h cavalier&mdash;
for whom, as I was waiting one night at the
garden-gate, another whom I &s;lighted ru&s;h'd in with
him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I fear the con&s;equence was fatal, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was indeed!&mdash;He, whom I had the lea&s;t
affection for, exa&s;perated by jealou&s;y and revenge,
immediately drew&mdash;They fought: he fell! Where|upon
the Engli&s;h gentleman pre&s;ently took hor&s;e,
and rode away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="142">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What cour&s;e cou'd you take in this extremity
of fortune?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! Madam, I was &s;o frighten'd, I knew
not what I did&mdash;I &s;hriek'd and cry'd for help when
it was too late&mdash;Thereupon a tumult aro&s;e&mdash;My
father call'd for me! In&s;tead of an&s;wering him, I
fled from his anger, and Theodo&s;ia conceal'd me
till I came here&mdash;The unhappy gentleman that was
vanqui&s;h'd, liv'd to tell who kill'd him, and the
cau&s;e; and by this time I believe is expir'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry for your misfortunes, and will
endeavour to moderate 'em&mdash;I know, my&s;elf, what 'ti$
to love again&s;t a father's will.&mdash;Therefore depend on
my a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I thank you; that's all that's in
my power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more ceremonies&mdash;You are Theodo&s;ia's
repre&s;entative of friend&s;hip, and as &s;uch I e&s;teem
you&mdash;Flora, &s;hew the lady in, and order Clara to
attend her&mdash;I wou'd not have my father &s;ee you, till
he has given leave to receive you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exeunt</HI> Fidelia <HI>and</HI> Flora.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Methinks I am touch'd for her misfortunes,
as if my own&mdash;Be&s;ides, who knows what the con|&s;equences
of my love may prove?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="23" REF="143">
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Flora.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My VEIL, Flora; I'll meet this cavalier in|&s;tantly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, beware of a di&s;covery by &s;o often
venturing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Too much caution is no good conduct in an
amour; for lovers have a thou&s;and artifices in the
wor&s;t of dangers.</P>
</SP>
<Q><L>In love and war we mu&s;t no fears betray,</L>
<L>Valour's the conduct that mu&s;t win the day.</L></Q>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>ACT II. SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A garden.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter Sir <HI>Charles,</HI> and <HI>A&s;pin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'TWAS excellent wine; and methinks
my mi&s;tre&s;s's health has &s;o elevated my fancy, that
it has in&s;pir'd me for the a&s;&s;ignation&mdash;Let me &s;ee,
'tis ju&s;t upon the time of the appointment&mdash;Where
have you been, &s;irrah?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Drinking the lady's health, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are a pretty fellow to toa&s;t that in|deed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="144">
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I gue&s;s'd you were at the &s;ame &s;port,
and that made me follow the example.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah, the airs of my conver&s;ation as
ill become one of your character, as tho&s;e of my
dre&s;s; but, like the vulgar in a factious country,
you love to ape the actions of your &s;uperiors.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, a valet claims as great a title to his
ma&s;ter's &s;econd-hand wit, as to his ca&s;t-off cloaths;
and cu&s;tom has equally made 'em the due perqui|&s;ites
of his place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Retire quickly&mdash;The lady's coming.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exit</HI> A&s;pin.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Leonora <HI>and</HI> Flora.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>Thus Sol, when he his amber beauty &s;hrouds,</L>
<L>Revives the flowers, tho' wrapt, like you, in clouds.</L>
<L>In beams that &s;tray, &s;ome cheerful influence &s;teals,</L>
<L>Till the kind God at length his rays reveals.</L>
</LG>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's more than I may chance to do, if
you are &s;o complai&s;ant as to mean me by the com|pari&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you may chance to do! I am very
glad, Madam, that you are &s;o dubious as to leave it
to chance. 'Tis po&s;&s;ible you may chance to be cruel,
but I hope that the probability is to the contrary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The probability depends indeed upon your
<PB N="25" REF="145">
hope&mdash;And lovers hopes are at be&s;t but &s;hadows of
thought, that produce no reality.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you are pleas'd to be witty,
and I admire you for it&mdash;But the &s;ight of you wou'd
make me your perfect adorer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye think there's no true love without
&s;eeing the object.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, certainly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>How d'ye think a blind man can be &s;en|&s;ible
of the pa&s;&s;ion, if he did not depend on his
imagination. Now, perhaps, were you to &s;ee me,
you'd no longer admire me; therefore I think you
had be&s;t remain as you are.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold; I forbid that, Madam&mdash;A blind
man can never hope to &s;ee the object of his affections,
and therefore can never expect to &s;atisfy his curio&s;ity
&mdash;But fight was given me to make u&s;e of&mdash;And
&s;hou'd I be &s;o contented, I &s;hou'd &s;uffer you to blind
my rea&s;on, as well as my eyes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can you be a lover, and pretend to the u&s;e
of rea&s;on&mdash;That's a contradiction in it&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not in the lea&s;t&mdash;'Tis a ranging un|&s;ettled
pa&s;&s;ion that's a contradiction to good &s;en&s;e&mdash;
But love and rea&s;on are in&s;eparable, like wit and
judgment&mdash;For as one is fond of the beauty, the
other di&s;tingui&s;hes the value of the ble&s;&s;ing, and
therefore knows how to prize it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="146">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Notwith&s;tanding your rhetoric, they are an
objection to each other&mdash;For according to the dictates
of love, I ought to grant your de&s;ires, and let you
&s;ee me&mdash;But &s;hou'd I now follow the maxims of
rea&s;on, I &s;hou'd remain in a cloud as I am&mdash;and
here break off our corre&s;pondence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I deny&mdash;For as love has prompted
you thus far, rea&s;on will &s;hew you 'tis too late now
to retire; therefore you &s;ee that every argument you
rai&s;e is an objection to your cruelty&mdash;Be&s;ides, when
we parted la&s;t, you promi&s;ed I &s;hould &s;ee you&mdash;And
I hope you will be as good as your word now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you know the promi&s;es of ladies, lovers,
and courtiers are &s;eldom of any effect&mdash;However,
I won't &s;tand with you for a trifle&mdash;How d'ye like
me?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Unveils.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am con&s;idering with my&s;elf, whether
you are an angel, or a woman&mdash;I thought &s;o much
wit cou'd not be ob&s;cur'd in a common form&mdash;And
now I &s;tand convinc'd in admiration.</P>
<STAGE>[Noi&s;e.</STAGE>
<P>Hey! What's the matter now?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>A&s;pin</HI> in a fright.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fly, Sir, fly immediately for your life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fly! prithee for what rea&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;P.</SPEAKER>
<P>We &s;hall only be hang'd, Sir, that's all, if
<PB N="27" REF="147">
we &s;tay&mdash;But I'll &s;ecure the garden-door to favour
our retreat, if there's any to be made.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Shuts the garden-door.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's the matter, fellow? are you mad?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mad! No, 'tis my ma&s;ter is mad to &s;tay
here&mdash;Leap over the wall&mdash;Fly any way, Sir, for
here's the governor with a whole troop of Jacks-in-office
at his heels come to &s;eize you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas, my father, Flora! undoubtedly he's
come thus on my account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure no man is &s;o unfortunate!&mdash;Can
love never come, but attended with cro&s;&s;es and di&s;|appointments?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir, don't talk of love now&mdash;Con&s;ider,
we are in danger of a halter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Force open the doors there.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Within.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, What d'ye mean? Love is always the
forerunner of mi&s;chief&mdash;A pox on it, our misfortune
came from love before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I am ruin'd if the governor &s;ees me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fair lady, I mu&s;t leave you, my life
depends on it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>And my honour&mdash;Hold; Can you be &s;o bar|barous
to leave me here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can you be &s;o barbarous to make us &s;tay
here, if you go to that.</P>
<STAGE>[Noi&s;e.</STAGE>
<P><PB N="28" REF="148">
Sir, make ha&s;te, or we &s;hall be too late.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay! I am greater than you think&mdash;'Tis for
me they come&mdash;And can you leave a woman in di&s;|tre&s;s?
think you my honour's nothing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing at all to compare with our lives&mdash;
<STAGE>[Noi&s;e again.</STAGE>
Sir, Are you mad? don't you hear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twas ungenerous in me to leave Fidelia
in danger&mdash;They &s;han't &s;ay I always &s;erve a woman
&s;o&mdash;Madam, my life &s;hall an&s;wer for your de&s;ence&mdash;
Go into that arbour, whil&s;t I guard the door.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exit</HI> Leonora. <HI>She drops her glove.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, &s;ince you are re&s;olv'd to be taken, Sir,
I'll not keep you company.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Goes to climb the wall.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come down you pigeon-hearted ra&s;cal,
and learn to &s;tand to a noble defence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, conduct is more requir'd than courage&mdash;
Therefore to run away will be the noble&s;t defence,
becau&s;e 'tis the wi&s;e&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Noi&s;e again.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>So! Now they come! the door is falling
from its hinges.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Lorenzo,</HI> Alguazil, and officers.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are not you, Sir Charles Winlove, an Engli&s;h
cavaller?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="149">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;corn to deny my name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Seize him! now to pri&s;on with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, con&s;ider, I'm no common per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know you are a man of quality, and as
&s;uch I &s;hall u&s;e you. Re&s;tore the gentleman his
&s;word&mdash;Where's the lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>The lady, &s;ay you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, the lady, Sir Charles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>A lady with me! What d'ye mean, my
lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>You need not deny it, I come well inform'd.
&mdash;Search about there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>What woman can it be that has brought
me into this misfortune?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[<HI>Officers find</HI> A&s;pin.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>What fellow's that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;ervant of mine, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Secure him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Sir, had not leaping over the wall,
and making to &s;ea, been a much better journey than
a ride to the gallows?&mdash;We had better have run the
ri&s;que of being pickled in &s;alt water, than of hang|ing
like a couple of &s;igns between earth and air;
you for a warning to all re&s;olute lovers, and I to &s;uch
&s;ervants as follow their ma&s;ters de&s;perate fortunes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>What glove's that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alg.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a lady's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="150">
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then 'tis probable &s;he can't be far off&mdash;
Search that arbour.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[<HI>They bring in</HI> Leonora <HI>veil'd.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am half dead with confu&s;ion&mdash;'Tis my
father! what can I expect?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alg.</SPEAKER>
<P>In a corner of the arbour we found this lady
&mdash;Unveil to my lord governor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you need not, for I know you
well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What does he &s;ay? Was ever woman &s;o
unfortunate!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;en&s;ible what courte&s;y I owe you&mdash;
Pardon the nature of my coming for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pardon me that &s;he does not go
with you&mdash;For &s;ingle as I am, and thus oppre&s;s'd
by odds, I had rather die, than &s;he &s;hou'd be a
&s;ufferer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generous cavalier!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is this the honourable u&s;e you make of the
re&s;toration of your &s;word?&mdash;But you &s;hall find we
can quell you, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, my lord, I know to oppo&s;e you
is to die; and that I can, with plea&s;ure, in vindication
of di&s;tre&s;s'd innocence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't think to deceive me! I know you
both&mdash;Her father's &s;o much my friend, I am equally
concern'd with him for her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="151">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The&s;e words confirm my fears! what &s;hall
I think or &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>U&s;e her well, my lord, that's all I a&s;k.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>My honour on her u&s;age.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, if our general comes to a parley, a
&s;urrender follows of cour&s;e&mdash;Sir, my courage is
rais'd at la&s;t, and &s;o let us e'en fight it out with 'em
now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I rely on your honour, and
&s;ubmit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I am lo&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep your &s;word &s;till&mdash;Here, take this gen|tleman
to the ca&s;tle&mdash;For the lady, &s;he &s;hall be in
my hou&s;e, and receiv'd there as my daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>As his daughter! I &s;ee now I am certainly
di&s;cover'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bring that fellow along&mdash;He &s;hall go with his
ma&s;ter&mdash;Hark you, a word with you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[To Alg.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, when I am in the humour of fighting,
'tis very hard to be given up a pri&s;oner, and have
my valour nipt in the bud.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, don't be dejected&mdash;Our next
meeting may be a turn of joy&mdash;And I hope this ad|venture
in the end will but prove like a little di&s;cord
in mu&s;ic, which rai&s;es it to a &s;weeter harmony.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, 'tis time for you to part&mdash;Mr. Al|guazil,
<PB N="32" REF="152">
di&s;po&s;e of the lady as I order'd you&mdash;Lead
on there.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt &s;everally.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter Flora.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>So! they are gone! I overheard all, and
'twas lucky they did not &s;ee me in the oppo&s;ite corner
to my lady&mdash;What woman wou'd tru&s;t an a&s;&s;ignation,
if this was always to be the con&s;equence?&mdash;But I mu&s;t
run home the back-ways, and prepare the family for
her reception.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II. The governor's hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter Don <HI>Philip.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! nobody to be found! Methinks
the hou&s;e looks as if the family had de&s;erted it&mdash;
Where can they all be gone?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Flora.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>So! thanks to my &s;tars, I have got home
before 'em&mdash;But I have run till I am quite out of
breath.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Starts.</STAGE>
<P>Don Philip!</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Flora, where are all the family?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lady is gone abroad.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where's my lord governor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="153">
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has ju&s;t now &s;ent an Engli&s;h cavalier pri|&s;oner
to the ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! an Engli&s;h cavalier! d'ye know
who he is?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>One Sir Charles Winlove, my lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Flora, that cavalier is my deare&s;t friend
&mdash;But wherefore do I loiter!&mdash;I'll fly this moment
to meet the governor, and try to intercede in his
behalf.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's one ob&s;tacle remov'd&mdash;But here they
come.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Alguzil,</HI> officers, and <HI>Leonora.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where's the lady Leonora? I have a me&s;&s;age
to her from the governor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What does the fellow mean?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's certainly &s;ome mi&s;take in this&mdash;I'll
humour it. [<HI>A&s;ide.</HI>] Perhaps it may prove a lucky
turn. The lady Leonora's friend is abroad, and
therefore you may leave your me&s;&s;age.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alg.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord governor has &s;ent this per&s;on a
pri&s;oner&mdash;But orders that your lady will take care
to have her us'd re&s;pectfully&mdash;So here my commi&s;&s;ion
ends, and I leave her to your charge.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are they gone?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="154">
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was never &s;o frighten'd in my life&mdash;What
excu&s;e &s;hall I make to my father? Certainly, he
knew me by what he &s;aid&mdash;And his caution to me
this morning confirms it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I rather believe, Madam, he mi&s;took you
for another; and, by all circum&s;tances, for the lady
you receiv'd to-day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! I have a thought&mdash;She &s;aid &s;he look'd
for an Engli&s;h cavalier that has kill'd a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, Madam, by the circum&s;tance of flying
from her father's hou&s;e, my lord governor may think
he has &s;eiz'd 'em together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If &s;o, I have a rival.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If &s;o, you'll come clear off, by turning it
upon her; I'll take away your VEIL, that you
mayn't &s;eem as if you had been abroad.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit, and returns.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou'rt a perfect Machiavel, Flora&mdash;I cou'd
no more part with thee, than I cou'd with my better
genius.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>A good &s;ervant is as great a jewel as a good
hu&s;band, Madam&mdash;And if you play your cards to
the be&s;t advantage, 'tis not in the power of fortune
to pique you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lee.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;hou'd I &s;erve the lady &s;o now I have
<PB N="35" REF="155">
receiv'd her, 'twill be a breach of friend&s;hip and
ho&s;pitality.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great &s;tate&s;men always &s;acrifice their friend|&s;hip
to their intere&s;t&mdash;Be&s;ides, &s;elf-pre&s;ervation is the
fir&s;t law of nature; and if you neglect this oppor|tunity,
you are ruin'd for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;till, methinks, I have &s;ome &s;cruples of
honour, Flora.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>A lady's honour, Madam, con&s;i&s;ts in her
reputation; and if you per&s;i&s;t, you'll &s;acrifice that
to the cen&s;ure of the world, and be oblig'd, like her
you have receiv'd, to fly from your father's hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, thou art an excellent ca&s;ui&s;t for the
&s;cruples of a tender con&s;cience&mdash;But if we &s;hou'd be
mi&s;taken in the lady, now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear, Madam&mdash;I heard my lord go|vernor
call the Engli&s;h cavalier by the title of Sir
Charles Winlove&mdash;Therefore, for better &s;atisfaction,
a&s;k her the name of her lover&mdash;Oh, here &s;he comes
opportunely to our purpo&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;ift her by degrees, that &s;he mayn't &s;u&s;|pect
me.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Fidelia.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you pre&s;s'd my &s;uit to the governor
yet, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="36" REF="156">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have not as yet had an opportunity; but
I expect him every minute to come home, and their
you may depend on't I'll u&s;e all my intere&s;t to &s;erve
you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee, Madam, you an&s;wer the character I
have had of you&mdash;for you differ from the ladies of
fa&s;hion, who, in&s;tead of pitying our &s;ex in misfor|tunes,
are the fir&s;t that reflect on 'em, and expo&s;e 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>None of our &s;ex are &s;o ungenerous, but &s;uch,
who, being guilty them&s;elves, wou'd endeavour to
hide their own frailties, by cen&s;uring the conduct
of others.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I e&s;teem it as the greate&s;t happine&s;s, that I
have met with &s;uch a comfortable refuge in the mid&s;t
of my misfortunes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am always, Madam, apt rather to a&s;&s;i&s;t a
lady in di&s;tre&s;s, than to reflect on her&mdash;But &s;hou'd
the governor comply with my reque&s;t, what farther
cour&s;es do you de&s;ign to take?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;earch out for the Engli&s;h cavalier, who,
I am inform'd, is here in Valencia&mdash;Otherwi&s;e, if
I &s;hould mi&s;s of him, I hear my friends are endea|vouring
to make my peace with my father; and as
he was ever fond of me, I hope his tenderne&s;s will
overcome his pa&s;&s;ion, and that he'll again receive
me as his child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="37" REF="157">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope all will turn to your advantage, Ma|dam
&mdash;But, in the mean time, what's the gentle|man's
name whom you are in &s;earch of?&mdash;Perhaps
I may learn where he is, if he's in Valencia?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>His name is Sir Charles Winlove.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Charles Winlove, &s;ay you! this increa&s;es
my misfortunes&mdash;Have I fo&s;ter'd a rival?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep your temper, Madam, and &s;tick to what
you propos'd; we'll find an after-plot to redeem all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>She changes colour! what can this mean?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Lorenzo,</HI> and <HI>Diego</HI> behind.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now you may return to Madrid, and inform
Alonzo that his daughter's &s;ecur'd in my hou&s;e, and
Sir Charles Winlove in the ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, my lord, I han't &s;een her yet, and
therefore can't affirm it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll call her then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hou'd rather be glad to &s;ee her, &s;o that
&s;he might not &s;ee me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold; there's my daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>And with her my lady&mdash;for &s;he on her left
hand is Fidelia.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, can you return with confidence?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dieg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can, my lord; farewel.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father approaches!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="38" REF="158">
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll retire, Madam, while you pre&s;s my &s;uit
to him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Going.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>What makes the lady &s;hun me, Leonora?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e &s;he's a &s;tranger, and that makes her
a little re&s;erv'd, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye remember my advice this morning,
daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now my fears!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Leonora, you may &s;ee the effect of
making private a&s;&s;ignations unknown to a father&mdash;
and of expo&s;ing a reputation, and the honour of
a family&mdash;What d'ye think will be the con&s;equence
of this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Of what, my lord!&mdash;I am di&s;cover'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Recollect the adventures of this morning,
and then you may gue&s;s at my meaning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee my &s;tratagems are in vain&mdash;My lord,
too well I under&s;tand you&mdash;And therefore throw me
at your feet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>She has di&s;cover'd all! what &s;hall we do now?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you mean! Are you at cro&s;s-pur|po&s;es,
child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I beg you hear me, and perhaps
I may give you &s;atisfaction.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Kneels.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e then; and if you intend to give me
<PB N="39" REF="159">
&s;atisfaction, let it be in a rea&s;onable an&s;wer&mdash;What
makes you in this confu&s;ion?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are you &s;o touch'd with yonder lady's misfor|tunes,
that you kneel in her behalf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, I am amaz'd! what an unexpected turn
is here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>The governor fixes his eyes on me!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am glad you are &s;o good-natur'd, Leonora!
for tho' that lady is a pri&s;oner, &s;he is the daughter
of my deare&s;t friend, and therefore I'd have her
us'd with &s;ingular re&s;pect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I in my &s;en&s;es! or do I dream!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Courage, Madam; all's well again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Apart.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I had like to have betray'd my&s;elf by my
timorous folly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>The governor approaches&mdash;I hope &s;he has
&s;ucceeded.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! here comes another turn of di&s;covery.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you are welcome to my hou&s;e&mdash;
I know your quality, and am &s;orry for this accident.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I thank you&mdash;You &s;ee me here a
&s;tranger in this place&mdash;therefore, to rai&s;e your pity
to my misfortunes, give me leave to relate their
particulars.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="160">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! if &s;he talks, &s;he betrays all&mdash;And then
we &s;hall be entirely undone.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know your &s;tory already, Madam&mdash;Our
hi&s;tories are full of &s;uch amorous adventures&mdash;but
I que&s;tion not, but your's will &s;hortly have a happy
end&mdash;In the mean time, this hou&s;e &s;hall rather be
your &s;anctuary than con&s;inement&mdash;Daughter, I re|commend
this lady to your conver&s;ation.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Excellently come off!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I find, Madam, by my &s;ucce&s;s, that you
have pleaded &s;trongly in my behalf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I even kneel'd to my father to &s;erve you,
and am glad it has lain in my power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you, Madam&mdash;I &s;hall never forget
&s;uch obligations&mdash;You'll excu&s;e me for retiring, for
I am impatient till I have writ an account of my
&s;ucce&s;s to Theodo&s;ia.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>It goes according to our wi&s;h&mdash;My father
&s;uppo&s;es 'twas her he &s;eiz'd with Sir Charles; and
&s;he knows nothing of her being a pri&s;oner, but is
pleas'd with her confinement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The end mu&s;t crown all, Madam&mdash;And if
you can carry on the mi&s;take&mdash;'twill be excellent
indeed! But how d'ye intend to proceed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e I write to Sir Charles?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ider, Madam, what you do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="161">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are the fir&s;t &s;ervant that ever was again&s;t
a lover&mdash;You &s;ee we are come well off&mdash;In love, as
in gaming, if we can make a &s;hift to &s;ave our&s;elves,
the hopes of winning is a temptation to play on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Madam, a little luck is commonly a
rook, that draws young game&s;ters in to their de|&s;truction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>A lucky ca&s;t is &s;eldom won by a faint heart&mdash;
Love is a lottery, and therefore&mdash;
<Q><L>As ventures only can our fortunes frame,</L>
<L>Tho&s;e who will nothing &s;take no prize can claim.</L></Q></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>ACT III. SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Lorenzo</HI> and Don <HI>Philip</HI> meeting.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>MY lord, you're well met&mdash;I am glad
I have the good fortune to light on you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you wanted me on any urgent occa|&s;ion?
Pray what may be the bu&s;ine&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have an humble petition to your lord|&s;hip,
and you mu&s;t promi&s;e me to grant it, before
I tell the con&s;equence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's very fine indeed! that I mu&s;t give my
con&s;ent, and not know to what&mdash;I &s;uppo&s;e this is
&s;omething in relation to my daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="42" REF="162">
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my lord; what I come now to reque&s;t
is in behalf of a friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be it as it will, Don Philip may command
me in any thing, as far as the rules of honour will
permit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, my lord, I &s;hall never be &s;o
ungenerous as to require any thing that wou'd be
a &s;tain to your honour&mdash;but my petition to you is in
behalf of Sir Charles Winlove, an Engli&s;h gentle|man,
who I am inform'd your lord&s;hip &s;ent this day
a pri&s;oner to the ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye know him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, my lord, and know him to
be a man of honour&mdash;I ow'd my life to him when
I was in England&mdash;and ever after there was &s;uch
a friend&s;hip between us, that during my continuance
there we were &s;eldom or never a&s;under.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am glad to hear &s;o honourable a character
of the gentleman&mdash;I am &s;orry for his misfortunes;
but he has injur'd a particular friend of mine in
relation to his daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, that proceeds from the wild|ne&s;s
of his youth&mdash;we are all &s;ubject to &s;uch
faults&mdash;Sir Charles is what we e&s;teem a fine gen|tleman;
and the Engli&s;h are all men of gallantry
and intrigue&mdash;Be&s;ides, if a young lady is inclinable
<PB N="43" REF="163">
to be kind, what bri&s;k cavalier can refu&s;e her fa|vours?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I cou'd &s;erve him with honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may: con&s;ider, to confine a young
gentleman from his plea&s;ures, is bla&s;ting him in the
bloom of his life&mdash;Be&s;ides, liberty is the very &s;oul
of the Engli&s;h, and they had rather &s;ubmit to ho|honourable
death, than bondage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can I do in this affair?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>If your lord&s;hip will allow him to be a
pri&s;oner at large, till you hear farther from Madrid,
my honour &s;hall be the pledge for his &s;ecurity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hou'd be willing to con&s;ent to this, were
I to follow my own inclinations&mdash;but his commit|ment
to the ca&s;tle is for murder.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I know the circum&s;tances of
the &s;tory, and the people concern'd in't, except the
young lady&mdash;therefore, if you $ll believe me, when
I left M$drid, the wounded cavalier was not actually
dead&mdash;nay, there was &s;ome hopes of his recovery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I had no &s;uch intimation in the letter I re|ceiv'd
this morning&mdash;but now I think on't, my
friend may write &s;o, becau&s;e I &s;hou'd &s;ecure his
daughter&mdash;Are you &s;ure of this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my honour, my lord, I am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then for once I'll yield to your de&s;ires&mdash;
<PB N="44" REF="164">
Follow me, and I'll give you my &s;ignet&mdash;The keeper
knowing you, will obey you at the &s;ight of it&mdash;But
remember I put my honour into your hands, there|fore
u&s;e it with di&s;cretion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, you may depend on it&mdash;Even
friend&s;hip it&s;elf &s;hou'd not win me to betray my
tru&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<DIV4 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE, The ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter Sir <HI>Charles</HI> and <HI>A&s;pin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly never man was &s;o unfortunate
&mdash;Sure the fates have join'd in con&s;piracy to plague
me in my amours&mdash;Nay, even the winds to com|pleat
my ruin have oppos'd my pa&s;&s;age to England&mdash;
A very fine comfort 'tis indeed&mdash;Here am I in con|finement,
without a friend to come to my a&s;&s;i&s;tance
&mdash;What the devil &s;hall I do in this exigence of
fortune!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, think Sir&mdash;we are in a fine place in|deed
&mdash;See what it is to be a great man! The
governor provides you with lodgings here in the
metropolitan ca&s;tle, where, for the &s;ecurity of your
per&s;on, he orders you a retinue of guards, as if
in the king's palace; but methinks the&s;e honours,
Sir, have a very &s;curvy countenance&mdash;Pray heaven
<PB N="45" REF="165">
we an't exalted to the highe&s;t <HI>po&s;ts</HI> of the na|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know what to think&mdash;The go|vernor
is certainly a man of quality, and can have
no other view in this than the &s;ervice of his country
&mdash;All that makes me dubious is, whether I am a
pri&s;oner for my own &s;ake, or the lady's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>For both, Sir; but here comes one that will
&s;olve the riddle&mdash;A woman in a VEIL&mdash;There's
certainly witchcraft in the&s;e women; for no &s;ooner
name a &s;he-devil, but you find her at your elbow.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Flora VEIL'D.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cavalier! I come from a fair lady that was
taken a pri&s;oner with you this morning&mdash;Read that.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Gives him a letter.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How does &s;he bear her confinement?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Like a turtle moaning for its mate&mdash;The
poor lady has fretted till &s;he's in the &s;pleen.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry that I &s;hou'd be the cau&s;e of
her misfortunes&mdash;But vexations in love are like
cloudy April &s;howers; they bring forth the flowers
of delight, to be chear'd by the warmth of the &s;un
in its full lu&s;tre&mdash;But now for the letter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>They &s;ay a witch commonly appears again&s;t
ill weather, like a porpus before a &s;torm&mdash;Now
<PB N="46" REF="166">
prithee, dam&s;el, what can we progno&s;ticate from the
&s;ight of you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prithee, fellow, learn more manners, and
to be le&s;s pert in your di&s;cour&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, if you talk of being pert, commend
me to a chambermaid, faith&mdash;But prithee, child,
don't affect the airs of your mi&s;tre&s;s thus&mdash;I an't &s;o
damnably in love with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your tongue, &s;irrah&mdash;My little
emi&s;&s;ary, tell the lady I'll wait on her at night
according to her command&mdash;till when, farewel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't fail.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll wait on her at night! Ha, ha, ha,
Sir, 'tis already dark&mdash;therefore, if you have the
keys of the ca&s;tle in your pocket, let us &s;hut the
doors after us, and take up with another new lodg|ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah, I have a key, and a gold one
too&mdash;Look here ra&s;cal&mdash;this, by the virtue of a
glittering &s;mile, can make the pri&s;on-doors fly open,
and turn confinement into liberty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, truly, it has an alluring look&mdash;but,
methinks, a little aqua fortis now wou'd be of much
more &s;ervice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you blockhead, d'ye think I in|tend
to apply it to the bars, to break jail?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="167">
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Sir, if you intend to keep your appoint|ment
with the lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I do intend to keep it, and there|fore
this goes to the keeper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>So it may&mdash;But I believe he has more wit
than to give you your freedom, if it does.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are mi&s;taken, &s;irrah&mdash;What! Can
it bribe a favourite to betray his prince, a &s;enate
their country, or a courtier his neare&s;t friend&mdash;yet
fail to tempt &s;uch fellows as jail-keepers to be per|fidious
to their tru&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>One que&s;tion more, Sir&mdash;Have you quite
forgot Fidelia?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>The ab&s;ence of an old mi&s;tre&s;s makes
room for a new one&mdash;Therefore I have blotted her
from my fancy, like a painter that &s;trikes one form
out of his cloth, to lay in another.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, con&s;ider, and don't run headlong thus
to your own de&s;truction.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Don <HI>Philip.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;pin turning philo&s;opher!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Don Philip, my &s;ervant ape, a
philo&s;opher, like a cobbler that leaves his &s;tall for a
tub, and &s;ets up for one of our reformed teachers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps he fancies him&s;elf in&s;pir'd, and
<PB N="48" REF="168">
thinks to deliver you by his in&s;piration to another
place&mdash;I'm &s;ure I'm &s;orry to &s;ee you where you
are.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don Philip, you are happy in the af|fections
of a fair lady&mdash;Therefore, let not your con|cern
for me be an interruption in your plea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>My mi&s;tre&s;s and my friend &s;hare my
heart&mdash;and I can never rejoice in one, when I am
concern'd for the other&mdash;Is there any thing I can
&s;erve you in?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is&mdash;You know I told you this
morning I had &s;truck up a new amour&mdash;I can't tell
you the lady's name, for &s;he's a &s;tranger to me&mdash;
But had I my liberty, I might have the happine&s;s
of &s;eeing her to-night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, Sir Charles&mdash;I find 'tis not
in the power of fortune to reclaim you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, faith; I am re&s;olv'd to overcome
her ill-nature by laughing at it&mdash;And let what will
happen, it &s;hall never alter my humour, nor be an
interruption to my plea&s;ures.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very finely re&s;olv'd indeed&mdash;But &s;uppo&s;e,
Sir Charles. I &s;hou'd gain you your freedom now,
what &s;ecurity &s;hall I have of your return?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the honour of an Engli&s;hman I'll
return again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="169">
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope he'll have more wit than to keep his
word though.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Enough&mdash;Here, who waits there?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Keeper.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye know this &s;ignet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Keep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, 'tis my lord governor's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I command you, by virtue of this, to
&s;hew that gentleman the &s;ame re&s;pect as to my&s;elf&mdash;
Give him his liberty&mdash;I'll an&s;wer it to the governor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Keep.</SPEAKER>
<P>I obey your orders.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, take this for your civility.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Keep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I thank you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now you have your liberty! You mu&s;t
take me along with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I won't draw you into dangers&mdash;
that wou'd be an ill return for &s;o great an obli|gation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>That excu&s;e won't &s;erve&mdash;I am re&s;olv'd
to &s;ee this mi&s;tre&s;s of yours, Sir Charles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't take it ill if I refu&s;e you&mdash;For
even Pylades and Ore&s;tes had their &s;eparate &s;ecrets
&mdash;This lady is a woman of quality, and, &s;hou'd
I &s;erve her &s;o, &s;he'll re&s;ent it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can you be &s;atisfied &s;he's a woman
of quality, if you never &s;aw her face?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="50" REF="170">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her manners and appearance are a con|vincing
proof of that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought, Sir Charles, you had known
the ways of your own country better&mdash;Perhaps &s;he
may be a courtezan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, I am convinc'd of the contrary
&mdash;Tho&s;e ladies are ea&s;ily di&s;tingui&s;h'd by their airs
from women of quality&mdash;You may depend on it I am
not &s;o ea&s;ily impos'd upon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't pre&s;s farther then again&s;t your
inclinations&mdash;Good night; I'll &s;ee you again to|morrow!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>So! Now fortune begins to turn her
wheel&mdash;Some lucky &s;poke may ri&s;e quickly to my
advantage&mdash;A&s;pin, lend me your pi&s;tol for my &s;e|curity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I &s;tay behind, Sir?&mdash;'Tis a &s;ervant's
duty to follow his ma&s;ter's heels&mdash;Be&s;ides, I don't
like this place for an amu&s;ement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come along then&mdash;It grows late, there|fore
I'll take a &s;hort turn, and wait for the happy
&s;ignal.</P>
</SP>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="scene">
<PB N="51" REF="171">
<HEAD>SCENE, The governor's hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Leonora.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The invention of a wit, the courage of a
knight-errant, and the conduct of a politician, are
all comprehended in an adventurous lover.&mdash;Fir&s;t
we lay the &s;cene of an a&s;&s;ignation; then enter into
the part, and if caught in the action, have a thou|&s;and
incidents to bring us off again.&mdash;I'm now
a&s;&s;ur'd, let what will interpo&s;e, love and re&s;olution
can never fail of &s;ucce&s;s.</P>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Flora.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Is the coa&s;t clear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam&mdash;The governor's gone to his
repo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where $word$ Fidelia?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the &s;ame condition.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>And Don Philip?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's ju&s;t come in, and retir'd to his apart|ment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are all the family at re&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="172">
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's not one &s;tirring in the hou&s;e,
Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;eek out for the cavalier.
<STAGE>[<HI>Exit</HI> Flora.</STAGE>
So! now I have nothing left me to fear, but a di&s;|appointment
from Sir Charles&mdash;Yet why that?
We young girls can break the pri&s;on of a father's
hou&s;e to fly to our admirers, therefore &s;uch a gallant
as he can never want a &s;tratagem to relea&s;e him|&s;elf&mdash;be&s;ides,
if Love's his guide, Fortune mu&s;t be
his a&s;&s;i&s;tant&mdash;but here they come.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Flora,</HI> and Sir <HI>Charles.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tread &s;oftly, Leonora's in the next room un|dre&s;&s;ing,
and the governor lies near.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thanks to my &s;tars, that thro' the folds
of darkne&s;s, I'm come, at length, to the regions
of light.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll retire, that I may give you notice if
any thing &s;hould happen.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad, this girl's worth gold&mdash;&s;he
knows civilly how to withdraw, and leave a pair
of lovers together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're a fine courtier truely, to let a
lady, when &s;he comes to &s;ee you, be carry'd away in
captivity&mdash;I thought by this time to have heard
<PB N="53" REF="173">
that you had broke your pri&s;on, &s;lain your guards,
and conquer'd whole armies to have gain'd my free|dom&mdash;then
you had been a lover indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I thought it wou'd be a much
greater plea&s;ure in a happy meeting to compleat my
ble&s;&s;ing, than to turn mad-man, and be run thro'
for aiming at impo&s;&s;ibilities.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a &s;atisfaction that every lover can
give, becau&s;e 'tis a plea&s;ure to him&mdash;but your
death wou'd have chronicled my fame in romance,
to have been read by young virgins in after-ages,
that &s;uch-a-one lov'd me &s;o, he dy'd for the &s;ake
of me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'e Madam, I am not &s;o romantic
as to die for the &s;ake of being read in a novel, to
divert girls in the green-&s;ickne&s;s&mdash;My intention
is to live for the end I was created, to propagate my
generation&mdash;therefore, as I am a pri&s;oner upon
parole, and mu&s;t return by break of day to the
ca&s;tle: let us reap the advantages of love, night,
and opportunity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>A fine &s;peech indeed! you are like the
athie&s;t, all for plea&s;ures at the pre&s;ent, and never
have a thought of futurity&mdash;I expected you wou'd
have prov'd a Paris, at lea&s;t&mdash;that is, have prof|fered
<PB N="54" REF="174">
to have carry'd me to a &s;afe harbour, and there
to have given your&s;elf up for life, as a per&s;onal
&s;ecurity for your love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>For life&mdash;too much re&s;embles marriage,
which is the di&s;agreeable part of love&mdash;be&s;ides,
my honour's engag'd for my return.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Love is the nice&s;t point of honour&mdash;there|fore
the engagement is of greater force&mdash;but I
know the rea&s;on why you are thus re&s;erv'd&mdash;you
have a pre-engagement on your heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis true, I have lov'd another; but
one love, like one power, yields to a &s;uperior.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, Sir Charles, I &s;ee you are too
incon&s;tant to be tru&s;ted&mdash;for now, by your own
confe&s;&s;ion, &s;hou'd you &s;ee another, I mu&s;t yield
your heart to her beauty, becau&s;e you may chance to
think it &s;uperior to mine</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, that's impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;for the
charms of your wit &s;o con&s;pire with tho&s;e of your
beauty, that they mu&s;t fix ev'n incon&s;tancy it&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I e&s;teem &s;uch flights but as compliments,
Sir Charles&mdash;and a compliment to a lady, like a
poetical flattering panegyric, is the &s;evere&s;t &s;atire&mdash;for
it &s;hows the per&s;ons what they ought to be in
the rever&s;e of what they are.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="175">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>What arguments can I then u&s;e to con|vince
you of my affections?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>None. I &s;hou'd as &s;oon take an athei&s;t for
a man of &s;en&s;e; a wit for a politician; or a politi|cian
for a man of honour; as a libertine, like Sir
Charles, for a lover.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Madam, can you have &s;o mean
an opinion of your own de&s;ert, as to believe a
heart that has been your captive, can ever break
your chains?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>No! but you have been fal&s;e already, and
incon&s;tancy is as bad a proof of love, as &s;eurrility
is of wit&mdash;the one proceeds from a fal&s;e genius,
and the other from a degenerate pa&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, this is trifling away the happy
minutes. [<HI>A pi&s;lol fir'd.</HI>] Ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What means that noi&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is certainly my dog of a &s;ervant!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Flora.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha&s;te, or you'll be di&s;cover'd; the gover|nor's
ri&s;ing!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where &s;hall hide my&s;elf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! here's no conveniency&mdash;therefore,
fly quickly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="56" REF="176">
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If he goes out at the door, the governor
meets him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;hall I do then!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Jacomo, Pedro, lights there!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Within.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>They're coming here!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there's no time to trifle!&mdash;Out, out of
window, Sir, quickly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Out of the window! &s;o, &s;hall I break
my neck, to pre&s;erve a lady's reputation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lights, lights there, quickly!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Within.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>For heav'n's &s;ake Sir Charles, fly! for my
honour, and your life!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fly! 'Sdeath, Madam, what do you
mean? D'ye think I have wings like a Cupid to
fly out of the window!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;tay will ruin me, Sir Charles!&mdash;be|&s;ides,
you may &s;afely get by a balcony, from my
clo&s;et into the court-yard!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>This comes now of making ill u&s;e of
of one's time, Well, I mu&s;t run the ri&s;que; but a
pox on me, if ever I draw my&s;elf into the&s;e &s;crapes
again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What cour&s;e &s;hall we take now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha&s;te to my daughter's chamber there.</P>
<STAGE>[Within.</STAGE>
<P>Some of you follow me, to &s;earch the court-yard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="177">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>H$rk! there are &s;ome of them coming here!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, then, out go the lights&mdash;Now, per|haps,
they'll conclude we are at re&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hiver with apprehen&s;ions&mdash;My father will
certainly find Sir Charles or his man in the court|yard!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>That we mu&s;t leave to fortune, Madam&mdash;
In the mean time, let us retire &s;oftly, for fear we
are di&s;cover'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter Sir <HI>Charles</HI> feeling his way.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vexations are always the fruits of an
intrigue&mdash;What &s;hall I do? Where's my ra&s;cally
&s;ervant? The hou&s;e is alarm'd, and I am in the
dark within the verge of the governor's palace!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>A&s;pin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have rais'd the hou&s;e with the report of
my pi&s;tol, and now &s;ecurity's the word&mdash;Odd, 'tis
very dark&mdash;Every &s;tep I have taken, I have knock'd
my head again&s;t &s;ome po&s;t or wall, till I have almo&s;t
beat out my brains.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I am not mi&s;taken, I hear the tread
of a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="178">
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>I warrant you now, my ma&s;ter is &s;o full of
his &s;port with the lady, that he hears nothing of
this di&s;turbance&mdash;Odd, I can but laugh to think
how he 'll look when he is catch'd in the nick of his
performance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's certainly &s;omebody in this yard&mdash;
If I don't take care, I may chance to lo&s;e my life
before I know where I am&mdash;therefore, old friend,
&s;tand to my a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark, I hear &s;omebody&mdash;they &s;teal &s;oftly,
thinking to catch me here before I am aware of
'em&mdash;The&s;e Spaniards are damn'd fellows&mdash;they
love to run a man thro' in the dark&mdash;Odd, I'll up
with my heels, and tru&s;t fear to be my guide&mdash;O
lud, I am caught! Help! help!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[<HI>Runs again&s;t Sir</HI> Charles.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whoever you are, if you offer to &s;tir an
inch, you 're a dead man.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Draws.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh lud, Sir, &s;ave my life, and I'll peach&mdash;
I'll tell you the whole plot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Is it your wor&s;hip, Sir?&mdash;This
is all owing to you, you ra&s;cal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you &s;earch'd every place carefully?
Follow me, &s;ome of you, to the court-yard.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Within.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad the enemy will be at our heels
pre&s;ently&mdash;Sirrah, march after me by the &s;ound
<PB N="59" REF="179">
of my tread&mdash;Ha! What have I &s;tumbled again&s;t?
A chair! It &s;eems &s;et in my way by fortune&mdash;
Lights are coming&mdash;I'll in here, and hide my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Opens the chair.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, let me come in too, for if I am taken,
I &s;hall either be hang'd like a dog, or knock'd o'the
head like an ox.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah, here's no room&mdash;therefore &s;hift
for your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Goes into the chair.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>They 're all coming; for heaven's &s;ake, let
me &s;it upon your knee, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get out you ra&s;cal, I &s;hall be di&s;cover'd
by your folly.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Shuts him&s;elf in.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is very barbarous&mdash;I wi&s;h I cou'd find
out a hor&s;e-pond&mdash;I'd run up to my neck to &s;ecure
my&s;elf&mdash;Here they come&mdash;If I am caught, I'll be
reveng'd and peach, I'm re&s;olv'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Lorenzo,</HI> and &s;ervants.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you been at Leonora's chamber?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t. <HI>Serv.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Lord&mdash;and I believe &s;he's in
her bed, for I &s;aw no light.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought I heard &s;omebody leap out of her
window&mdash;Secure the gates.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="60" REF="180">
<STAGE>Enter Don <HI>Philip.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don Philip! Have you caught the alarm
too?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, I heard a noi&s;e in my room,
and came to &s;ee what's the matter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>We thought &s;omebody had broke in&mdash;but
we can find no one but our own family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you made a diligent &s;earch, my
Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>We have &s;earch'd almo&s;t every where&mdash;ex|cept
any one's hid in that chair.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me the light, I'll &s;ee&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Opens the chair, Sir <HI>Cha.</HI> nods at him to take no notice.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is there any one?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my Lord&mdash;Death and confu&s;ion!
Sir Charles there!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twas a mi&s;take betwixt &s;leep and waking&mdash;
I'll retire to re&s;t again&mdash;A good repo&s;e to you
Don Philip.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>The like to your Lord&s;hip.&mdash;
So, they are all retir'd now, to their re&s;pective
chambers&mdash;My Lord, would have per&s;uaded me
this was an illu&s;ion&mdash;So he thinks to deceive me,
whil&s;t I deceive him&mdash;We wou'd both hide the
<PB N="61" REF="181">
di&s;grace from each other.&mdash;Hi&s;t, Sir Charles
you may come forth now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Philip thou art the be&s;t of friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I not? to be made a property to my
own &s;hame: Is this generous u&s;age?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>What mean you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have &s;upplanted me in Leonora.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a mi&s;take&mdash;I came to a young
Lady that's a pri&s;oner&mdash;who was taken with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's a poor eva&s;ion, and below a
man of honour&mdash;I know the rea&s;on now, why you
refus'd to admit of my company&mdash;be&s;ides, there's
no &s;uch per&s;on in the hou&s;e&mdash;Look'e, Sir Charles,
I &s;hall expect &s;atisfaction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'e, you are mad&mdash;for jealou&s;y
is no other than madne&s;s&mdash;I tell you there is &s;uch
a lady; perhaps, you may be &s;o blinded with love,
that you may not regard any body in the family but
the governor and his daughter&mdash;but if what I &s;ay
is not true, to-morrow you &s;hall have what &s;atis|faction
you require.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Till then farewel.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farewel, till you come to your &s;en&s;es
again&mdash;So! I have brought my&s;elf to a fine pa&s;s
indeed&mdash;I have kill'd one hot-brain'd fool for his
jealou&s;y, and now to compleat my misfortune, he
<PB N="62" REF="182">
too has catch'd the infection&mdash;What &s;hall I do?
If I &s;tay here and tru&s;t the inqui&s;ition, 'tis ten times
more unmerciful than a Middle&s;ex jury&mdash;A man
can never have fair play for his life&mdash;to touch cold
iron, and come off like a gentleman&mdash;Shall I then
lay hold on this opportunity, and make my e&s;cape!
No! They &s;hall never &s;ay an Engli&s;hman's &s;o ba&s;e
a coward.</P>
</SP>
<Q><L>Let the hot Spaniard boa&s;t his virtue here,</L>
<L>And honour's lo&s;s in jealous notions fear.</L>
<L>A Briton &s;corns to prove his country's &s;hame,</L>
<L>And rather hazards life, than taints his &s;ame.</L></Q>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>ACT IV. SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The governor's hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Leonora <HI>and</HI> Don Philip.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>COME, come Madam, I'm not to be
&s;o impos'd upon! you may deny it as long as you
plea&s;e, but you can't per&s;uade me out of my &s;en&s;es
&mdash;Did not I, la&s;t night, actually &s;ee Sir Charles hid
under your window in the court-yard?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e you did, Sir?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="63" REF="183">
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Madam, I can &s;uppo&s;e it to be
no advantage to your character&mdash;S'death, am I to
be made a property! a mere pander! to carry on
an intrigue again&s;t my own honour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well! go on, Sir, go on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>So I can, Madam. Is it prudent for a
young lady, ju&s;t upon her marriage, to entertain a
cavalier alone at midnight&mdash;nay, in her own
chamber too! unknown to her father, or any one
that &s;hou'd be the guardian of her honour?&mdash;Such
conduct is mighty reputable indeed, Madam!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e &s;uch a per&s;on was here, Sir&mdash;is
there no other place that cou'd entertain him but
my apartment?&mdash;Am I the only per&s;on he cou'd
come to?&mdash;Mu&s;t I be accountable for his being
here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Madam, by no means&mdash;'Tis pro|bable
to believe a per&s;on of his quality, might have
an affair with one of your &s;ervants only&mdash;S'death,
d'ye take me for a fool! is there any other young
lady in the hou&s;e? Look'e, Madam, I &s;hou'd not
&s;o tamely take this of Sir Charles, but that I &s;corn
to in&s;ult a man in his misfortunes&mdash;however, I can
be yet capable of re&s;entment&mdash;for know, I'll im|mediately
demand my contract of your father, and
return back to Madrid.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Going.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="64" REF="184">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I let him go, this may give room for &s;u&s;pi|cion,
and &s;u&s;picion will bring a di&s;covery.
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
Hold, Sir&mdash;Not that 'tis worth my while to clear
my innocence, for your &s;ake, but for my father's:
Know then, here is another young lady in this
hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye! who? tell me that pray, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The pri&s;oner, Sir&mdash;I &s;hall have a fine time
to &s;atisfy your &s;cruples.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>The pri&s;oner! ha, ha, ha! you are
both in the &s;ame &s;tory, I find&mdash;your &s;cheme is ex|cellently
well laid&mdash;Were I a zealous dotard, or a
Briti&s;h hu&s;band, perhaps I might be credulous enough
to believe any thing&mdash;but this deceit won't take;
it won't, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! what indecency have I been guilty
of to merit this u&s;age?&mdash;but know, &s;ince you are
&s;till re&s;olv'd to traduce my honour, there are tho&s;e,
Sir, that will vindicate it&mdash;This is not to be borne
with patience!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Madam, don't di&s;order your&s;elf
thus&mdash;for you may henceforth meet Sir Charles
as often as you plea&s;e&mdash;and expo&s;e your reputa|tion
as much as you think fit; it &s;hall never give me
any further unea&s;ine&s;s I can a&s;&s;ure you, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="65" REF="185">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;olent! before you had re&s;olv'd to treat
me after this manner, you might, at lea&s;t, have
a&s;k'd my father if there was no &s;uch per&s;on in
the hou&s;e!&mdash;Is this the return for all his friend|&s;hip?
But here comes the lady her&s;elf, I &s;hall leave
her to give you &s;atisfaction.&mdash;Provoking man!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! what do I &s;ee? Here comes a young
lady indeed! I'm afraid jealou&s;y has carry'd me
too far&mdash;Soft! I'll lay a&s;ide this heat a little, if
po&s;&s;ible.&mdash;
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Fidelia.</STAGE>
But &s;till methinks my choler ri&s;es &s;o, I know not
how to &s;uppre&s;s it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Leonora, <HI>and</HI> Flora <HI>behind.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here we may learn their di&s;cour&s;e. Me|thinks,
tho' I am partly in fault, I am exa&s;pe|rated
at &s;uch treatment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! who's here? What can be the mean|ing
of this!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Madam, don't &s;tart&mdash;I hope the
&s;ight of me has not put you in a con&s;ternation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I came to meet a friend, and being
lo&s;t in thought, pardon me, if I was a little &s;ur|priz'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="66" REF="186">
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, whoever you came to meet,
and however &s;trange it may &s;eem to you, you are
the only per&s;on I cou'd wi&s;h for at pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me, Sir! I don't know that ever I &s;aw
you in my life before!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very like &s;o, Madam&mdash;But however
you may be &s;urpriz'd, you have been the cau&s;e that
has rais'd this di&s;order in my &s;oul, and 'tis in your
power alone to appea&s;e it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I the cau&s;e of your di&s;order, Sir!&mdash;certainly
the man's mad!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, if my temper's a little
ruffled.&mdash;Perhaps I may be impertinent&mdash;but if
you have the lea&s;t compa&s;&s;ion, I beg you an&s;wer me
to one particular.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart, Sir, if it lies in my
power.&mdash;What can the man mean! He looks as
if he was di&s;tracted!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>An&s;wer me directly and &s;incerely, Madam
&mdash;for my &s;cruples are as of great a con&s;equence,
as tho&s;e of troubled minds, that apply to ca&s;ui&s;ts
for ea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, you &s;urprise me wonderfully&mdash;What
&s;atisfaction can I, that am a &s;tranger, give you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>The greate&s;t! and only in one trivial
an&s;wer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="67" REF="187">
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is it, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye know &s;uch a per&s;on as Sir Charles
Winlove, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir! your que&s;tion &s;tartles me, in|deed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>It need not; for, as I am a cavalier, I
a&s;k you for no treacherous de&s;ign&mdash;therefore be
kind, and ca&s;e me with an an&s;wer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>How earne&s;t and concern'd he &s;eems! Sure
he has no de&s;ign to offer love&mdash;Perhaps he may
come as a &s;py to betray me&mdash;I know not what to
think.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I conjure you by all the &s;oft|ne&s;s
of your &s;ex, to free me from my doubts&mdash;
for the whole quiet of my &s;oul depends on what
you &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will&mdash;whate'er the con&s;equence may
prove, I leave to you&mdash;Know then, I &s;corn on any
terms to deny my affection for Sir Charles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;atisfaction cheers me indeed!&mdash;
Cur&s;e on my jealous folly!&mdash;Are you a native of
Valencia, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, I am totally a &s;tranger to it&mdash;
Love, that has been my guide to ruin, was my
directer hither.&mdash;But now, Sir, an&s;wer me a que&s;tion
<PB N="68" REF="188">
in my turn.&mdash;Are you acquainted with Sir
Charles?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, if they come to particulars, we are
lo&s;t again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I know him well&mdash;He is my
deare&s;t friend.&mdash;How have I wrong'd him with
&s;u&s;picions!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your friend, &s;ay you! Can you give me
any tidings of him, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I que&s;tion not, but he is return'd in &s;afety
to the ca&s;tle&mdash;I am now immediately going to him
about &s;ome affairs of con&s;equence; in the mean
time depend on my intere&s;t to &s;erve you both.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the ca&s;tle! &s;aid he &s;o, or did I dream?
Oh! for the wings of Love to ha&s;te and be con|vinc'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Going.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, here's another hare &s;tarted&mdash;Where are
you going in &s;uch ha&s;te, Fidelia?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Comes forward.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I hear that the cavalier, that I'm
in &s;earch of, is a pri&s;oner in the ca&s;tle; therefore,
I mu&s;t immediately fetch my VEIL, and ha&s;ten to
&s;ee him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now am I more unfortunate than ever!&mdash;What
&s;top &s;hall I put to this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you mu&s;t again con&s;ult your wit:
you &s;ee di&s;coveries gather like clouds, and I'm
<PB N="69" REF="189">
afraid the main &s;torm will come rattling upon us
immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was never &s;o provok'd in my life, as I was
at Don Philip's jealou&s;ies, and all this I undergo
for a per&s;on that I'm not &s;ecure of&mdash;For as Fide|lia
was the fir&s;t object of Sir Charles's affections,
&s;he'll &s;till be the mi&s;tre&s;s of his heart&mdash;and po&s;|&s;e&s;&s;ion
there, as in the law, will make her eleven
points before me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Madam, in my humble opinion,
'twill be better to drop this amour&mdash;This lady will,
in the end, di&s;cover all&mdash;therefore, I think it
better to for&s;ake a victory than to lo&s;e it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am of the &s;ame opinion&mdash;But what &s;hall
I do in this affair?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>E'en follow the example of declining cour|tiers&mdash;that
is, whil&s;t you've po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of his affec|tions,
think 'tis more honour to re&s;ign than to be
remov'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I mean, now I have gone &s;o far, how
&s;hall I retire without hazarding my reputation?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shou'd you tru&s;t his love, even the &s;ucce&s;s of
your amour will be of ill con&s;equence&mdash;Therefore,
appoint another a&s;&s;ignation with him&mdash;let her into
the &s;ecret, &s;o far as not to give her unea&s;ine&s;s, and
carry her with you to meet him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="70" REF="190">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prudently advis'd&mdash;But &s;ee, &s;he comes: I
mu&s;t not let her go, for that will ruin all.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Fidelia.</STAGE>
<P>Are you re&s;olv'd upon this adventure, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: now I know where Sir Charles is,
methinks, I am all impatience to &s;ee him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'd advi&s;e you to apply your&s;elf to &s;econd
thoughts, and ere you fix upon a re&s;olution, to
weigh well the con&s;equence of this proceeding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>The con&s;equence!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye: con&s;ider, you are no more mi&s;tre&s;s
of your liberty&mdash;but are here now in confinement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>In confinement, Madam! I de&s;ire you to
explain your meaning?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, in &s;hort, to clear up the my&s;tery at
once; my father is an intimate friend of yours&mdash;and
for the &s;ake of that friend&s;hip, he has here en|gag'd
to &s;ecure you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I &s;o barbarou&s;ly betray'd then! I
thought, Madam, I had come to the governor's
daughter for refuge, and not to a pri&s;on to be con|fin'd
in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't but make an allowance to your &s;ur|prize&mdash;and,
therefore, yield to your re&s;entment.
<PB N="71" REF="191">
But I could wi&s;h, you wou'd make your&s;elf a little
ea&s;y&mdash;for, perhaps, I might yet propo&s;e a method
for your &s;atisfaction.&mdash;Ha! my father! for hea|ven's
&s;ake calm your&s;elf a little.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Lorenzo.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>What makes the lady appear in &s;uch a di&s;|order,
Leonora?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now the cloud is gather'd, it begins to
break before we are prepar'd for't.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>A trifle only, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Madam, 'tis no trifle&mdash;My lord, I
think I have rea&s;on to be &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Madam!&mdash;I hope you have receiv'd
no ill-treatment from any of my family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The lady was going abroad without your
leave, and I believe &s;he may take it ill, becau&s;e I
told her the con&s;equence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Madam! I am &s;orry you &s;hou'd be
led into &s;uch an error.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I confe&s;s a point of ceremony
might have oblig'd me to a&s;k'd your leave&mdash;but
either there is a mi&s;take on your &s;ide: or if you
rightly knew me, and the cau&s;e why I am here,
I believe you wou'd not refu&s;e me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="72" REF="192">
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis becau&s;e I know both, Madam, I do re|fu&s;e
you&mdash;and tho' you may command what free|dom
you plea&s;e in the hou&s;e, I beg you &s;till to re|member
you're a pri&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>A pri&s;oner! Upon what account? By what
authority, my lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, my authority was never wont to
be call'd in que&s;tion&mdash;be&s;ides, I thought I had
&s;atisfy'd you as to that, when I &s;eiz'd you ye&s;terday
with Sir Charles Winlove.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Seiz'd me ye&s;terday with Sir Charles Win|love!
What does your lord&s;hip mean?&mdash;In &s;hort, I
believe you're impos'd upon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, if my &s;en&s;es are right, I am cer|tain
I am not impos'd upon&mdash;and you mu&s;t pardon
me, if I can't con&s;ent to be &s;o&mdash;Did not I bring
you ye&s;terday here in cu&s;tody?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my lord: this lady and her &s;ervant,
can witne&s;s I came here alone, and on my own
accord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>To contradict the fair, may &s;eem a breach
of re&s;pect due to the &s;ex&mdash;therefore, I can make
you no other an&s;wer than this, that when young
ladies are in love, 'tis no wonder if they are thus
forgetful.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="73" REF="193">
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I de&s;ire that you'll &s;peak, and
&s;atisfy my lord as to your knowledge in this affair.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you &s;ee my lord is already &s;atis|fy'd
&mdash;Be&s;ides, &s;ince you are wound in the toil,
I &s;han't draw my&s;elf into the &s;nare to deliver you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, this is very hard, thus to be &s;hut
out of the light of rea&s;on, to remain in the dark|ne&s;s
of my&s;tery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ser.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come along there&mdash;bring him before my
lord governor.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Within.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! what new di&s;turbance is this?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter &s;ervants with <HI>A&s;pin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gentlemen, dear gentlemen, don't collar
me &s;o furiou&s;ly&mdash;con&s;ider, to choke a man with|out
a halter is again&s;t law&mdash;be&s;ides, I am no Turk,
and therefore am not ambitious of the honour of
being &s;trangled like a Grand Vizier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! 'tis Sir Charles's man&mdash;perhaps this
may be of an ill con&s;equence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let go your hold of him. What's the mean|ing
of all this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t <HI>Serv.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, this is the fellow that made the
di&s;turbance la&s;t night&mdash;for, &s;earching him, we found
this pi&s;tol conceal'd in one of his pockets.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="74" REF="194">
<SPEAKER>2d <HI>Serv.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, we believe he came upon a very
traiterous de&s;ign&mdash;for we di&s;cover'd him hid under
one of the maids beds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very pretty fellow indeed!&mdash;Take him
away, I'll con&s;ider of a puni&s;hment for the ra&s;cal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is an admirable place for law and
di&s;cipline&mdash;Prie&s;ts enjoin penance for lenten mor|tification,
and judges hang folks without hearing
their defence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye you pre&s;ume to murmer in my pre|&s;ence,
&s;irrah? What have you to &s;ay for your|&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say! why nothing, my lord! I am unpro|vided
with coun&s;el, and therefore, my motion is,
that I may defer my trial.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prithee, fellow, an&s;wer me to the pur|po&s;e
&mdash;What are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not guilty, my lord; not guilty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mean, &s;irrah, who are you? What's your
bu&s;ine&s;s here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, as to who I am, I am my ma&s;ter's
&s;ervant; and as to my bu&s;ine&s;s here, if you don't
like my company, I am ready to take my leave.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Going.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop him:&mdash;I never &s;aw &s;o impudent a fel|low
before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="75" REF="195">
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>They &s;ay, Madam, he's an Engli&s;hman's
&s;ervant; but I'm &s;ure he has an Iri&s;h a&s;&s;urance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray heav'n he has a&s;&s;urance enough to
bring him&s;elf off; for I'm afraid this will open the
&s;cene, and immediately di&s;cover all.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'e fellow&mdash;give &s;ome account of your|&s;elf;
what profe&s;&s;ion are you of?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my lord, I wait upon my ma&s;ter&mdash;
In his chamber I'm his valet in ordinary; &s;ometimes
his pimp in extraordinary; and commonly, have the
honour to be of his cabinet council.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou art an excellent ra&s;cal, indeed!&mdash;
Prithee, fellow, who is your ma&s;ter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>So! the&s;e great folks are as forgetful of
every thing, as they are of their promi&s;es&mdash;Is then
my face a &s;tranger to your lord&s;hip?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah, if you had gold enough in your
pocket to an&s;wer the bra&s;s of your countenance,
you might outvie the mo&s;t impudent courtier in
Europe&mdash;but don't pre&s;ume to trifle with me thus
any longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then to refre&s;h your memory, my lord,
I am Sir Charles Winlove's &s;ervant, and your lord|&s;hip's
pri&s;oner at di&s;cretion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! I had forgot the rogue, indeed!&mdash;So,
Madam, does the &s;cene now begin to open or not?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="76" REF="196">
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I am innocent of the charge; and
therefore, am &s;atisfy'd this can have no relation to
me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis well, Madam; this will appear imme|diately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm afraid, Flora, now come$ the clue that
will unravel the my&s;tery at once.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the fir&s;t place, ra&s;cal, what provok'd you
to make &s;uch a di&s;turbance?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my lord, I was a&s;&s;aulted in your lord|&s;hip's
court-yard by a great ma&s;tiff, and I u&s;ed that
pi&s;tol as an in&s;trument to allay hi$ fury.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the mean time, where was your ma&s;ter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only playing a game or two, with my lady,
my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, Madam!&mdash;Go on, &s;irrah.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, my lord, I know no more, than that
he was carried away from me by a &s;he-confident of
the lady's, vulgarly call'd a chamber-maid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's a treacherous rogue!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! Flora&mdash;did you conduct him to the
lady's chamber?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I, my lord!&mdash;Certainly the fellow has
not the impudence to &s;ay &s;o!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, I had not &s;uch cat's eyes to know any
one in the dark; but methinks your voice agrees
<PB N="77" REF="197">
much with that pert lady's that brought the letter
to my ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, this ra&s;cal will betray all!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then this was a concerted bu&s;ine&s;s, I find.
&mdash;Sirrah, let me hear no more of the&s;e practices.&mdash;
Di&s;charge the fellow, and let him return to his
ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, they &s;ay, confe&s;s and be hang'd!&mdash;But
I am come as clear off by turning evidence, as if I
had bought off the verdict of a jury.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, Madam, I hope now you'll no longer
deny your corre&s;pondence with Sir Charles Win|love
&mdash;But I am &s;orry, for the &s;ake of my re&s;pect
to your father, to &s;ee you &s;till &s;o regardle&s;s of your
honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, believe me, I am innocent&mdash;
and if Sir Charles has had any affair here&mdash;'tis
with &s;ome of your own family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cou'd almo&s;t wi&s;h to be ignorant of &s;uch
convincing proofs in relation to this affair&mdash;but you
mu&s;t pardon me, if I grow now to be more cautious
of your proceedings&mdash;Flora, &s;hou'd I find you in
the lea&s;t concern'd in this, you &s;hall no longer re|main
in my hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now is my time!</P>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;Methinks your
countenance, Madam, &s;peaks a &s;urprize at the&s;e
proceedings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="78" REF="198">
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I own I am &s;o confus'd, that I &s;carce know
whether this is reality, or an illu&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee, Fidelia, you are a little acquainted
with the artifices of love, tho' you are caught in
the &s;nare&mdash;Can't you dive into the my&s;tery of this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>An ignorant innocence is peculiar to our
&s;ex; and to dive into my&s;tery, they &s;ay, is a &s;in in
any one but a brother of the profe&s;&s;ion&mdash;therefore,
I &s;hall let it re&s;t, till it unravels it&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Were I in your ca&s;e, I &s;hould rather be fired
with a woman's curio&s;ity, than be &s;o unmov'd at
the turns of my fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am already &s;atisfy'd of my misfortunes;
therefore, curio&s;ity might betray me to a knowledge
that, perhaps, wou'd heighten 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas, Fidelia! I am in as great a concern
as you are&mdash;for my quiet is equally at &s;take with
yours&mdash;but if you will con&s;ent to come into my
mea&s;ures, there is yet a way to make us both ea&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Propo&s;e it: for methinks I cou'd embrace
any method that cou'd bring me to the &s;ight of Sir
Charles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know then, my father has contracted me
to one, who has all the qualities that can make him
agreeable&mdash;notwith&s;tanding which, I have lately
entertain'd the addre&s;&s;es of an Engli&s;h cavalier, who
now proves to be the very &s;ame you were &s;peaking
of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="79" REF="199">
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! Sir Charles Winlove, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! after having ruin'd me, can he be
&s;o perfidious to make his addre&s;&s;es to another!&mdash;Fal&s;e
man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas, all men are the &s;ame, Fidelia!&mdash;In
&s;hort, they u&s;e us as children do their toys; are
fond of us at fir&s;t&mdash;but quickly neglect us to fol|low
new fancies.&mdash;But to proceed&mdash;Ye&s;terday, I
met this Sir Charles at his lodgings, where my
father came, attended with officers, and &s;eiz'd us to|gether!
&mdash;He was carry'd to the ca&s;tle, and I was
brought home conceal'd in a VEIL; where, by the
circum&s;tances of the &s;tory, I find he mi&s;took me for
you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wou'd you be willing, Madam, to re&s;ign
your intere&s;t in Sir Charles, provided I would &s;tand
to the re&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Fidelia, you &s;hall now &s;ee me throw
off the &s;oftne&s;s of a lover for the craft of a poli|tician,
to &s;erve you&mdash;And a$ a fir&s;t proof of my
friend&s;hip, I'll write to him as from my&s;elf: Flora
&s;hall carry the letter; and if he can get his liberty,
I'll engage he &s;hall meet us in two hours at ano|ther
place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is as I cou'd with, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="80" REF="200">
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>One thing more.&mdash;I overheard your di&s;|cour&s;e
with that cavalier who is to be my hu&s;band&mdash;
I &s;ee his jealou&s;ies are cur'd, and all points are
now clear'd to my content.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fide.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let us then be quick in our proceedings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Leo.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart&mdash;we'll now retire,
and I'll write immediately to Sir Charles.&mdash;Flora,
be ready within call to attend us.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flo.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, my lady is now come off again to
her &s;atisfaction.&mdash;If our &s;ex were as prudent in
re&s;olution, as they are quick at invention, they
would not prove &s;uch weak fools to the men.&mdash;
However, I have learnt now, if occa&s;ion &s;erves,
to carry on an intrigue of my own&mdash;for I find,
tho' dangers happen from love, wit never fails to
turn the tables upon fortune.</P>
</SP>
<Q><L>Thus, when from fate our di&s;appointments fall,</L>
<L>Woman's invention can o'ercome 'em all.</L></Q>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="81" REF="201">
<HEAD>ACT V. SCENE I.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The governor's hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter Lorenzo and Alonzo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>MY old friend, once more I congratulate
your arrival to Valencia&mdash;You are come in good
time to vindicate the honour of your family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come in a good time, &s;ay you! No, I
am come in a very ill time, I can't &s;o much as
thank you for your civility.&mdash;Hark'e, prithee
look in my face now&mdash;Am not I very much alter'd?
Have not I &s;omething very rueful in my counte|nance?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>What makes you fancy &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e, methinks, I am no better than a
raven, I can croak nothing but bad news.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, be cheerful; all will go well
again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, truly! all is like to go mighty well,
indeed!&mdash;My &s;on-in-law, that was to be, has been
de&s;perately wounded; my daughter's run away,
and my family's di&s;graced for ever; and you expect
me to be cheerful, do you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but hear rea&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="82" REF="202">
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but I won't hear rea&s;on! What
have I to do with rea&s;on, when I come in &s;earch
of revenge?&mdash;You &s;ay, you have 'em both in your
cu&s;tody!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e I have! You tell me the wounded
cavalier is recovered, then what pretence can I have
for detaining Sir Charles?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter&mdash;I 'll conceal his recovery, and
have the dog &s;uffer for his death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fye! I am a&s;ham'd to &s;ee your pa&s;&s;ion &s;o
overcome your rea&s;on&mdash;Suppo&s;e your daughter loves
him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Loves him! 'Sdeath, who doubts but &s;he
does love him!&mdash;What, becau&s;e the &s;illy baggage
has been &s;o weak as to &s;uffer him to ruin her, you
would have me play the old dotard, and be as great
a fool as my daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Still you mi&s;take me.&mdash;Why will you en|deavour
thus to widen the breach, when I wou'd
bring matters to a reconciliation?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>To a reconciliation!&mdash;Ha, ha, ha! this is
plea&s;ant, indeed!&mdash;The &s;on of a whore has &s;tole
away my daughter, and for ought I know, &s;he may
have her belly up to her mouth; and you talk of
bringing matters to a reconciliation!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;uppo&s;e &s;he &s;hou'd love him; and he
&s;hou'd have an equal pa&s;&s;ion for her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="83" REF="203">
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, my cur&s;e be an equal portion
for them both!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps, he wou'd con&s;ent to marry her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marry her! no, no, no! The young fe|llows
of this age, are not &s;uch fools as to debauch
women, and afterwards to marry 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but I know what it is to be a young
fellow! I tell you their vows always di&s;&s;olve with
virginities, and when the fort's &s;urrender'd, all for|mer
promi&s;es are void o' cour&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>There are, indeed, too many of the fair &s;ex
in that unhappy condition; but why &s;hou'd you
judge &s;o hardly of your daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;hou'd I not judge for Did &s;he not
run away with him? Has &s;he not a $anguine com|plexion,
and he a brawny back? Is &s;he not a pro|mi&s;ing
girl, and he a &s;prightly young fellow?&mdash;
Then, why may not my daughter happen to be with
child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Still you perplex your&s;elf with fancied in|juries
only&mdash;Was &s;he ever loo&s;e in her behaviour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I always believ'd her to be a very
mode&s;t girl: But now, &s;he has certainly ta&s;ted of the
tree of knowledge&mdash;he has open'd her &s;en&s;es, and
enter'd her into her rudiments.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you ever love your daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="84" REF="204">
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, too well; tho' indeed, &s;he was a
very good girl, and de&s;erv'd it&mdash;Nay, now I
think of her, the tears of affection &s;till come into
my eyes!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indulge that tenderne&s;s, and rea&s;on will
come o' cour&s;e&mdash;D'ye think I am your friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>How &s;hou'd I know that? We were friends
once, indeed!&mdash;That is, when we were young&mdash;
Then we us'd to drink our bottle together, ruin'd
as many girls, and made as many cuckolds as any
rake-hells in Europe&mdash;But now, the &s;cene i$
chang'd: you are my lord governor! time, ab|&s;ence,
and &s;tate-affairs may have drove me out of
your memory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, you &s;hall &s;ee I am &s;till your friend:
have patience, and I'll endeavour to bring all to
a right under&s;tanding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Patience!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay, &s;uppre&s;s your choler, 'till you &s;ee
whether you have rea&s;on for it&mdash;I'll now imme|diately
go, and propo&s;e an honourable treaty to Sir
Charles: in the mean time I beg you to reti$e, and
not &s;ee your daughter 'till I return to tell you my
&s;ucce&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your return will bring me a fine account
of &s;ucce&s;s, indeed!&mdash;We men are certainly mo&s;t
<PB N="85" REF="205">
unhappy wretches&mdash;When we are young, we get
children in the heat of our blood, who, when we
come to be old, grow di&s;obedient, and break our
hearts in order to get into our e&s;tates&mdash;Well, I'll
&s;ay no more, but I'll &s;end this rebel daughter of
mine to a nunnery, and there &s;he &s;hall mortify for
the &s;ins of the fle&s;h&mdash;but for that rogue that has
debauch'd her, if ever I &s;ee him again, I'll have
his blood, tho' I meet him in a &s;anctuary.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<DIV4 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE, The ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter Sir Charles Winlove and Don Philip.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Charles, I am now convinc'd of
your innocence&mdash;My &s;u&s;picions were the fond er|rors
of my love, and as &s;uch I hope you 'll e&s;teem
'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do; when I con&s;ider that jealous eyes
always &s;ee thro' a micro&s;cope, that magnifies the
meane&s;t tri&s;les, to &s;eem as of the greate&s;t con&s;e|quence
&mdash;but had you not been my friend, I
&s;hou'd not &s;o tamely have &s;ubmitted to &s;uch u&s;age.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I own the ra&s;hne&s;s of my folly to be
great&mdash;Let fools have the ob&s;tinacy to perfi&s;t in
their errors&mdash;a generous &s;oul e&s;teems it rather as a
point of honour, when convine'd, to acknowledge
<PB N="86" REF="206">
'em.&mdash;Therefore, now let us turn the di&s;cour&s;e&mdash;
I'll a&s;&s;ure you, Sir Charles, I think the captive is
very beautiful.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beautiful as ever I &s;aw!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;till, methinks, my lady excels her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Every lover is apt to think his own
mi&s;tre&s;s the mo&s;t de&s;erving&mdash;Mine has wit as well
as beauty; and where the lu&s;ciou&s;ne&s;s of one may
cloy the appetite, the other whets it again, and
makes all her charms as agreeable as ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wit and beauty are two irre&s;i&s;tible wea|pons,
indeed; but, I find, you are in a fair way
to &s;ucceed in your hopes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, faith&mdash;Notwith&s;tanding &s;he has
&s;o many perfections, my &s;ucce&s;s was but very in|different:
whether the incon&s;tant &s;tar that governs
the &s;ex rul'd, I know not; but my reception prov'd
as great a di&s;appointment, as the accident after|wards
did a &s;urprize.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, that was a meer feint, only to make
a trial of your love! I find you are not rightly ac|quainted
with the variety of a lady's humour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, nor ever &s;hall, if 'tis &s;o much ad|dicted
to whim&s;ey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>But a lover &s;hou'd make it his bu&s;ine&s;s,
fir&s;t, to &s;tudy the temper of his mi&s;tre&s;s, and then
to &s;tudy every method that may promote her
plea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="87" REF="207">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I am not &s;o much a lover as to
&s;ubmit my rea&s;on to frenzy&mdash;For to &s;tudy the tem|per
of a woman, is like &s;earching out for the phi|lo&s;opher's
&s;tone&mdash;a man may &s;pend his e&s;tate, run
mad, and grow never the wi&s;er.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Notwith&s;tanding your har&s;h cen&s;ure of
the &s;ex, I wi&s;h I knew the humour of my lady, &s;o
far as to gain remi&s;&s;ion for my &s;olly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, this is ever the con&s;equence of jea|lou&s;y
&mdash;Fir&s;t, you quarrel with your mi&s;tre&s;s for
no rea&s;on, and then are never ea&s;y till you're re|concil'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>I own it is a weakne&s;s, indeed; but a
Spaniard is &s;o unfortunate in his pa&s;&s;ions, that he
can no more avoid the ra&s;hne&s;s of jealou&s;y, than
he can expel the heat of his climate.&mdash;But what
&s;ervice, Sir Charles, can I do you now in your
amour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, once more to tru&s;t you as a
friend, I have this day receiv'd a letter from the
lady:&mdash;but &s;ure there are &s;uch beauties in the &s;tyle!
not Ovid is more &s;oft, nor Horace more &s;a$irical.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>What are the contents of it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a kind invitation to another ap|pointment;
but $nter&s;pers'd with reflections from
an excellent talent of wit in relation to my &s;ervant's
<PB N="88" REF="208">
carele&s;&s;ne&s;s:&mdash;Here, prithee read it, and give
me your opinion.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter A&s;pin.</STAGE>
<P>So! Where have you been, &s;irrah?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I have run thro' as dangerous adven|tures
as a knight-errant&mdash;but as I was prede&s;tinated
to act the part of champion, I was prepar'd with
armour accordingly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Were you &s;o? Prithee, let's hear the
wonderful de&s;cription of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Sir, courage was the &s;upport of my
back; caution the defence of my brea&s;t; wit was
my noble head-piece; and this pi&s;tol, the weapon
with which I encounter'd death and de&s;truction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>That pi&s;tol, &s;irrah! What occa&s;ion had
you la&s;t night to make it give &s;uch an alarm?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Sir, I was a&s;&s;aulted by no le&s;s than
a fiery dragon&mdash;In &s;hort, a great ma&s;tiff flew at
my throat, and had I not had the courage to have
encounter'd his fury, I had certainly been torn in
pieces.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay then, Sir Charles, you mu&s;t never
be angry with him for his valour&mdash;A&s;pin has now
rival'd the fame of St. George&mdash;and I think his
&s;tatue ought to be &s;et up in memory of this atchieve|ment,
as a &s;econd honour to your country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="89" REF="209">
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is pa&s;t, was but a trial for the courage
of a hero&mdash;But the next misfortune I fell into, re|quir'd
the deepe&s;t policy of a &s;tate&s;man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye! prithee what was that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was this morning di&s;cover'd by &s;ome of
the &s;ervants, and carry'd, <HI>vi &amp; armis,</HI> a pri&s;oner
before my lord governour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye! How came you off there, A&s;pin?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir, I brought my&s;elf off with a wet
finger!&mdash;Fir&s;t, the governour a&s;k'd me &s;everal
que&s;tions&mdash;I generou&s;ly told him the affair you
had la&s;t night with the lady&mdash;confe&s;&s;ion merited
mercy, and I was immediately di&s;charg'd like a
man of honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Were you &s;o, &s;irrah? Know then, ra&s;|cal,
you have di&s;cover'd all my de&s;igns, and I'll
this moment make an example of you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, Sir Charles&mdash;con&s;ider, his folly
is below your re&s;entment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have &s;carce patience to &s;uffer the dog
in my &s;ight&mdash;Ra&s;cal! deceitful villain!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is this the return for all the dangers I have
&s;uffer'd&mdash;Well, 'tis an ungrateful age&mdash;but I am
not the fir&s;t man of merit that has been &s;lighted after
his faithful &s;ervice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="90" REF="210">
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, be pacify'd Sir Charles&mdash;all
may be ea&s;ily brought off again.&mdash;Here, take
your letter: I have read it, and approve of the de|&s;ign.
&mdash;But have you prepar'd any place for your
appointment with the lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, as to that part, I believe, I mu&s;t
rely upon you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I can help you at a dead lift&mdash;
My apartment has a door into another &s;treet&mdash;
Order her to be carry'd the back-way, and as
&s;he's a &s;tranger to the place, &s;he may be ea&s;ily de|ceiv'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I like the propo&s;al well.&mdash;A&s;pin, go
you this moment and conduct 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>A&s;p.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, tho' we men of merit are &s;o barba|rou&s;ly
us'd, we are always wanted in a ca&s;e of
nece&s;&s;ity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sirrah, no prating; mind what I &s;ay,
and go out of my &s;ight. [<HI>Exit</HI> A&s;pin.] Now which
way &s;hall I obtain my liberty for this adven|ture?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I'll gain you that freedom&mdash;and
that you may the better by day-light pa&s;s unknown,
I'll &s;end you my cloak, and you &s;hall muffle
your&s;elf in that&mdash;Ha! the governour! What
means this?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="91" REF="211">
<STAGE>Enter Lorenzo.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don Philip, I &s;ee your friend&s;hip is not like
that of the world, a meer counterfeit profe&s;&s;ion&mdash;
for you endeavour to &s;erve the per&s;on you value,
tho' you &s;ee him loaded with affliction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, friend&s;hip is only &s;hew'd in
adver&s;ity: a man in pro&s;perity has abundance of
profe&s;&s;ors&mdash;but had he need of one, not a friend
among&s;t 'em all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your friend&s;hip is mutual&mdash;Sir Charles
&s;av'd your life, and you 'd now return it with the
pre&s;ervation of his&mdash;&s;o that you both are exceptions
from the general rule of the world; for there's
&s;carce a per&s;on in it, be&s;ides your&s;elves, can &s;ay,
I have a friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e the rever&s;e of friend&s;hip is the
product of a degenerate age; where hone&s;ty pa&s;&s;es
for folly; perfidiou&s;ne&s;s for good policy; and all
manner of knavery, for nece&s;&s;ary wi&s;dom to thrive
in the world.&mdash;So that a man can no more be
a&s;&s;ur'd of friends in adver&s;ity, than a king or coun|try
in di&s;tre&s;s&mdash;when tho&s;e that &s;hou'd be &s;o, en|rich
them&s;elves in their de&s;truction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are a young Stoic indeed, Sir Charles&mdash;
However, I come now to &s;tand your friend, for
<PB N="92" REF="212">
want of pity, in your ca&s;e, wou'd be downright
cruelty&mdash;and therefore, give me leave to make
&s;ome propo&s;als that may be to your &s;atisfaction&mdash;
Don Philip, I hope you'll excu&s;e me a little.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I take my leave&mdash;Hark'e,
Sir Charles, what &s;hall I do in this affair?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go, and detain the lady till I come&mdash;
and d'ye hear, leave orders with the keeper for my
freedom.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Phil.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear&mdash;I'll manage all to the be&s;t
advantage.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have this morning receiv'd advice of the
cavalier's recovery, that was thought to have been
kill'd&mdash;This I mu&s;t yet keep as a &s;ecret, till I
have brought matters to bear.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, my lord, if you plea&s;e, I am
ready to receive your propo&s;als.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Charles, I am come to you concerning
an affair of con&s;equence.&mdash;You mu&s;t know, Alon|zo,
the father of Fidelia, and I, when young,
were never &s;eparated from each other&mdash;Now, I
under&s;tand by a letter from Madrid, you have late|ly
depriv'd him of his daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! depriv'd him of her, my lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye; but methinks I would willingly heal
this breach&mdash;therefore I'd advi&s;e you to find &s;ome
<PB N="93" REF="213">
means, by which you might reconcile your&s;elf to
him, and re&s;tore the honour of the young lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I under&s;tand you not&mdash;'Tis
true, I love Fidelia as my life; but for her honour,
it is not in the lea&s;t forfeited on my account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her father is of a quite contrary opinion.&mdash;
Therefore, if you have either a value for your&s;elf,
or an affection for the young lady, you will con&s;ent
to tho&s;e means, that will contribute to her ea&s;e, as
well as to your own &s;ecurity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I own the wildne&s;s of my
youth.&mdash;But I have &s;o true an affection for Fidelia,
that for my &s;ecurity, I prize it not in compari&s;on
with her content.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee, Sir Charles, you begin to gue&s;s at
my meaning&mdash;Therefore I que&s;tion not but to
find you the man of honour, I was apt at fir&s;t &s;ight
to believe you&mdash;Her &s;ame upon your account is
very much become the di&s;cour&s;e of the world&mdash;
therefore to reconcile all, wou'd you be willing to
accept her for a wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I needed not this preparation
to embrace &s;uch welcome propo&s;als.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ent to that, and I'll engage your par|don
&s;hall be &s;ecur'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My life is of as little value to me now,
as when I ran the ri&s;que of forfeiting it for her&mdash;
<PB N="94" REF="214">
But for the loo&s;er wi&s;hes that my incon&s;tancy has
been guilty of, cou'd I be &s;o happy to &s;ee her, they
wou'd immediately vani&s;h at her &s;ight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know then, Sir Charles, the lady is &s;till in
Valencia.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! in Valencia, my lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>She has remain'd in confinement at my
hou&s;e, ever &s;ince I ye&s;terday &s;eiz'd her at your
lodgings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, then there is a mi&s;take in this&mdash;
The lady that was taken with me, I can a&s;&s;ure
you, is not Fidelia.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her father's &s;ervant cou'd not be mi&s;taken,
and he afterwards &s;aw her at my hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know her face too well to be deceiv'd&mdash;
The lady that was taken with me, I was a &s;tranger
to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a pretty contrivance indeed!&mdash;
In the fir&s;t place, the young lady owns her&s;elf to
be Fidelia, but at the &s;ame time denies a corre&s;|pondence
with you&mdash;and now you own a corre&s;|pondence
with her, but deny &s;he is the per&s;on&mdash;
Who was it then that you had an a&s;&s;ignation with
la&s;t night at my hou&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Since you have made a di&s;covery in
that affair, 'twa$ with the lady that was &s;eiz'd
with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="95" REF="215">
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>And that lady, you po&s;itively &s;ay, is not
Fidelia?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, my lord, and if I am in my
&s;en&s;es, I am &s;ure I can affirm it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now &s;he actually &s;ays &s;he is&mdash;but denies
that &s;he has either &s;een you, or had any di&s;cour&s;e
with you in Valencia.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, then, there is a farther my&s;tery in
this!&mdash;I am certain, the lady I met la&s;t night was
not Fidelia.&mdash;Now if the per&s;on you mean, that
denies all this, &s;hou'd prove to be her, then your
lord&s;hip is mi&s;taken, for &s;he can't be the &s;ame that
was &s;eiz'd with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, there has been no art magic to tran&s;|form
her, nor to change one per&s;on to another.&mdash;
Therefore depend on't, &s;he's the &s;ame&mdash;Now the
me&s;&s;enger from her father went away &s;atisfy'd &s;he
was the right; and &s;he, upon examination, own'd
her&s;elf to be &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>This makes it all &s;eem more intricate
&s;till.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come with me, and let your &s;ight convince
you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>By this he'll di&s;cover the lady is gone
abroad, in order to meet me&punc;&mdash;What can I do?
I mu&s;t &s;ubmit.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="96" REF="216">
<SPEAKER>Lor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come along then, Sir Charles&mdash;methinks
I am impatient to have this riddle explain'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I the like, my lord&mdash;for I am
&s;ure, as the &s;tory lies now, there is &s;o great a my|&s;tery
in it, 'tis beyond the power of a churchman
to unfold it, till we &s;ee farther.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
